ched= 30\n|Total ships cancelled=\n|Total ships active= 30<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.janes.com/article/87014/type-052d-destroyer-and-type-054a-frigate-enter-service-with-plan |title=Archived copy |access-date=21 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306234754/https://www.janes.com/article/87014/type-052d-destroyer-and-type-054a-frigate-enter-service-with-plan |archive-date=6 March 2019 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|Total ships laid up=\n|Total ships lost=\n|Total ships retired=\n|Total ships preserved=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Header caption = \n| Ship type = [[Frigate]]\n| Ship displacement = 4,053 tonnes (full) (CCTV report)\n| Ship length = {{convert|134.1|m|ft|abbr=on}} (CCTV report)\n| Ship beam = {{convert|16|m|ft|abbr=on}} (CCTV report)\n| Ship draught = \n| Ship draft = \n| Ship propulsion = [[CODAD]], 4 \u00d7 [[Shaanxi Diesel Engine Factory|Shaanxi]] 16 PA6 STC diesels, 5700 kW (7600+ hp @ 1084 rpm) each\n| Ship speed = 27 [[knot (unit)|knots]] estimated\n| Ship range = {{convert|8025|nmi|mi km}} estimated\n| Ship complement = 165\n| Ship sensors = *[[Type 382 Radar]]\n*[[Type 344 Radar]] (Mineral-ME ''Band Stand'') OTH target acquisition and SSM fire control radar\n*4 \u00d7 [[Type 345 Radar]](MR-90 ''Front Dome'') SAM fire control radars\n*[[Type 360 Radar|MR-36A]] surface search radar, I-band\n*Type 347G 76 mm gun fire control radar\n*2 \u00d7 [[Decca Radar|Racal]] RM-1290 navigation radars, I-band\n*MGK-335 medium frequency active/passive sonar system\n*[[Naval weaponry of the People's Liberation Army Navy#Sonars|H/SJG-206]] [[towed array sonar]]\n*ZKJ-4B/6 (developed from [[Thomson-CSF]] TAVITAC) combat data system\n*HN-900 [[Data link]] (Chinese equivalent of [[Link 11]]A/B, to be upgraded)\n*SNTI-240 [[Communications satellite|SATCOM]]\n*AKD5000S Ku band [[Communications satellite|SATCOM]]\n| Ship EW = *Type 922-1 [[radar warning receiver]]\n*HZ-100 [[Electronic countermeasures|ECM]] & [[ELINT]] system\n*Kashtan-3 missile jamming system\n| Ship armament = *1 \u00d7 32-cell [[Vertical launching system|VLS]]\n** [[HQ-16]] [[Surface-to-air missile|SAM]]\n** [[CY-1#Yu-8|Yu-8]] anti submarine rocket launcher\n*2 \u00d7 4 [[C-803]] anti-ship / land attack cruise missiles\n*1 \u00d7 PJ26 76 mm dual purpose gun\n*2 \u00d7 [[Type 730]] 7-barrel 30 mm CIWS guns or [[Type 730 CIWS#Type 1130|Type 1130]]\n*2 \u00d7 3 324mm [[Yu-7 torpedo|Yu-7]] [[Anti-submarine warfare|ASW]] [[torpedo]] launchers\n*2 \u00d7 6 Type 87 240mm anti-submarine rocket launcher (36 rockets carried)\n*2 \u00d7 Type 726-4 18-tube decoy rocket launchers\n| Ship armour = \n| Ship armor = \n| Ship aircraft = 1 [[Kamov]] [[Ka-28]] 'Helix' or [[Harbin]] [[Harbin Z-9|Z-9]]C\n| Ship aircraft facilities = [[hangar]]\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''Type 054A''' (NATO codename '''Jiangkai II''') frigate is a class of [[People's Republic of China|Chinese]] multi-role [[frigates]], the first of which entered service with the [[People's Liberation Army Navy Surface Force]] in 2007. It is a development of the [[Type 054 frigate]], using the same hull but with improved sensors and weapons.\n\nThe Type 054A was first revealed while under construction at the [[Guangzhou]]-based Huangpu Shipyard in 2005.\n\n==Improvements over Type 054==\nThe Type 054A carries [[HQ-16]] medium-range air defence missiles and anti-submarine missiles in a [[vertical launching system]] (VLS) system. The HQ-16 has a range of up to 50&nbsp;km, with superior range and engagement angles to the Type 054's [[HQ-7]]. The Type 054A's VLS uses a hot launch method; a shared common exhaust system is sited between the two rows of rectangular launching tubes.<ref>\u8230\u8f7d\u6b66\u5668SHIPBORNE WEAPONS 2013 AUGUST ISSUE</ref>\n\nThe four [[AK-630]] [[close-in weapon system]]s (CIWS) of the Type 054 were replaced with two [[Type 730 CIWS]] on the Type 054A. The autonomous Type 730 provides improved reaction time against close-in threats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mil.jschina.com.cn/huitong/Jiangkai_Jiangwei.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-03-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070107054058/http://mil.jschina.com.cn/huitong/Jiangkai_Jiangwei.htm |archivedate=7 January 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Type 054A retains its predecessor's stealth features, including sloped hull design, radar absorbent materials, and a clean profile.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sinodefence.com/navy/surface/type054a-jiangkai-ii.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-03-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AEmfuBHt?url=http://www.sinodefence.com/navy/surface/type054a-jiangkai-ii.asp |archivedate=27 August 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Type 054A+==\nAn improved variant beginning with the 17th unit<ref name=\"navyreco24june17\">[http://navyrecognition.com/index.php/news/defence-news/2017/june-2017-navy-naval-forces-defense-industry-technology-maritime-security-global-news/5314-china-s-24th-type-054a-frigate-commissioned-with-plan-south-sea-fleet.html China's 24th Type 054A Frigate Commissioned with PLAN South Sea Fleet] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170627003729/http://www.navyrecognition.com/index.php/news/defence-news/2017/june-2017-navy-naval-forces-defense-industry-technology-maritime-security-global-news/5314-china-s-24th-type-054a-frigate-commissioned-with-plan-south-sea-fleet.html |date=27 June 2017 }} \u2013 Navyrecognition.com, 24 June 2017</ref> launched from Huangpu Shipyard in 2009<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110620183842/http://www.china-defense-mashup.com/pla-navys-type-054a-frigate-to-be-launched-in-guangzhou.html 1st Type 054A+ launched]</ref> has the seven-barrelled [[Type 730 CIWS]] replaced by the more capable 11-barrelled [[Type 730 CIWS#Type 1130|Type 1130]], and is unofficially referred as '''Type 54A+'''.<ref>\n{{Cite web\n |url         = http://tuku.military.china.com/military/html/2015-01-12/228714_2592892.htm\n |title       = \u4e2d\u56fd\u6d77\u519b054A+\u7248\u62a4\u536b\u8230\u66dd\u5149\uff1a\u6362\u88c51130\u8fd1\u9632\u70ae\uff01(by anonymous author, with other person's photograph)\n |page        = 4\n |language    = Chinese\n |publisher   = \u4e2d\u534e\u7f51\n |access-date = 23 February 2017\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304100823/http://tuku.military.china.com/military/html/2015-01-12/228714_2592892.htm\n |archivedate = 4 March 2016\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref> Another reported improvement over the original Type 054A includes the incorporation of [[variable depth sonar]] and towed array sonar.<ref>\n{{Cite web\n |url         = http://tuku.military.china.com/military/html/2015-01-12/228714_2592897.htm\n |title       = \u4e2d\u56fd\u6d77\u519b054A+\u7248\u62a4\u536b\u8230\u66dd\u5149\uff1a\u6362\u88c51130\u8fd1\u9632\u70ae\uff01(by anonymous author, with other person's photograph)\n |page        = 9\n |language    = Chinese\n |publisher   = \u4e2d\u534e\u7f51\n |access-date = 23 February 2017\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304100829/http://tuku.military.china.com/military/html/2015-01-12/228714_2592897.htm\n |archivedate = 4 March 2016\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Operations==\nType 054A frigate made its first operational deployment to the [[Gulf of Aden]], when 570 ''Huangshan'' set sail as part of 2nd Escort Flotilla/Task Group 167 on 2 April 2009, the Escort Flotilla arrived there on 13 April 2009, and took over form 1st Escort Flotilla/Task Group 169 on 15 April 2009. Since then, 11 Type 054A have deployed to the Gulf of Aden for anti-piracy operations.\n\nIn the lead-up to the [[Libyan civil war]], 530 ''Xuzhou'' was deployed from anti-piracy operations in the Gulf of Aden to help evacuate Chinese nationals from Libya.\n\nIn January 2014, 546 ''Yancheng'' was redeployed from anti-piracy operations in the Gulf of Aden to the eastern [[Mediterranean Sea]] to [[convoy|escort]] [[Syria]]n [[chemical weapon]]s [[Destruction of Syria's chemical weapons|destined for destruction]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Chinese-warship-in-Cyprus-to-aid-Syrian-chemical-weapons-removal-337057 | title=Chinese warship in Cyprus to aid Syrian chemical weapons removal | date=4 January 2014 | newspaper=Jerusalem Post | author=Reuters | accessdate=22 April 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422231655/https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Chinese-warship-in-Cyprus-to-aid-Syrian-chemical-weapons-removal-337057 | archive-date=22 April 2019 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Export==\n\nAccording to an estimate by ''[[The Diplomat]]'', Type 054A frigates have a per-unit cost of US$348 million.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://thediplomat.com/2016/12/china-commissions-new-stealth-warship-into-east-sea-fleet/ |magazine=[[The Diplomat]] |first=Franz-Stefan |last=Gady |title=China Commissions New Stealth Warship Into East Sea Fleet |date=29 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230152742/http://thediplomat.com/2016/12/china-commissions-new-stealth-warship-into-east-sea-fleet/ |archive-date=30 December 2016 |quote=The Binzhou is the 23rd Type 054A frigate on active duty with the PLAN and constitutes the cornerstone of China\u2019s surface warfare capabilities. The PLAN expects to commission another four Type 054 frigates by 2018. According to a cost estimate published in The Diplomat, the per unit price is set at around $348 million.}}</ref>\n\n===Pakistan===\nThe [[Pakistan Navy]] ordered four Type 054As; the last two orders were announced on 1 June 2018. The ships are expected to enter service by 2021.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rahmat |first1=Ridzwan |title=Pakistan signs for two more Type 054A frigates from China |url=https://www.janes.com/article/80571/pakistan-signs-for-two-more-type-054a-frigates-from-china |date=3 June 2018 |access-date=24 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125030920/https://www.janes.com/article/80571/pakistan-signs-for-two-more-type-054a-frigates-from-china |archive-date=25 November 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The steel-cutting ceremony for the second Type 054A frigate for the Pakistan Navy (PN) was held in China on 19 December 2018, marking the beginning of construction of the vessel at the Hudong-Zhonghua shipyard in Shanghai.\n<ref>{{cite web |title=China begins work on Pakistan\u2019s second Type 054A frigate |url=https://www.janes.com/article/85384/china-begins-work-on-pakistan-s-second-type-054a-frigate |date=21 December 2018 |access-date=21 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181221131249/https://www.janes.com/article/85384/china-begins-work-on-pakistan-s-second-type-054a-frigate |archive-date=21 December 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On November 1, 2019, China\u2019s Hudong-Zhonghua Shipbuilding held a steel cutting ceremony for the Pakistan Navy\u2019s third and fourth Type 054A frigates. The induction of these vessels could significantly enhance the service\u2019s anti-air warfare capabilities.<ref>{{cite web |title=China cuts steel for Pakistan\u2019s third, fourth Type 054A frigates {{!}} Jane's 360 |url=https://www.janes.com/article/92328/china-cuts-steel-for-pakistan-s-third-fourth-type-054a-frigates |website=www.janes.com |access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref> The keel-laying ceremony for the second ship was held on March 23, 2019 at Hudong Zhonghua shipyard in Shanghai.<ref>{{cite web |title=China lays keel for Pakistan Navy\u2019s second Type 054A-class frigate |url=https://www.janes.com/article/95109/china-lays-keel-for-pakistan-navy-s-second-type-054a-class-frigate |website=www.janes.com |access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Thailand===\nIn January 2013, it was confirmed that China offered to sell three Type 054As to the [[Royal Thai Navy]] for US$1 billion.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Grevatt |first1=Jon |title=China offers Type 054 to meet Thai frigate requirement |url=http://www.janes.com/products/janes/defence-security-report.aspx?ID=1065975734&channel=defence&subChannel=business |date=30 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130607150716/http://www.janes.com/products/janes/defence-security-report.aspx?ID=1065975734&channel=defence&subChannel=business |archive-date=7 June 2013 |access-date=24 November 2018}}</ref> Instead, Thailand selected a derivative of the [[South Korea]]n {{sclass-|Gwanggaeto the Great|destroyer|1}} from [[Daewoo Shipbuilding & Marine Engineering]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rahmat |first1=Ridzwan |title=DSME launches Thailand's first multipurpose frigate |url=http://www.janes.com/article/67140/dsme-launches-thailand-s-first-multipurpose-frigate |date=23 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170124182358/http://www.janes.com/article/67140/dsme-launches-thailand-s-first-multipurpose-frigate# |archive-date=24 January 2017 |access-date=24 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Ships of Class==\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse;\"\n|- style=\"background:#069;\"\n|'''<span style=\"color:#fff;\">&nbsp;Pennant Number&nbsp;</span>'''\n|'''<span style=\"color:#fff;\">&nbsp;Name&nbsp;</span>'''\n|'''<span style=\"color:#fff;\">&nbsp;Builder&nbsp;</span>'''\n|'''<span style=\"color:#fff;\">&nbsp;Launched&nbsp;</span>'''\n|'''<span style=\"color:#fff;\">&nbsp;Commissioned&nbsp;</span>'''\n|'''<span style=\"color:#fff;\">&nbsp;Fleet&nbsp;</span>'''\n|'''<span style=\"color:#fff;\">&nbsp;Status&nbsp;</span>'''\n|-\n|515<ref name=\"Rahmat_2016-12-30\">{{cite web |url=http://www.janes.com/article/66605/china-commissions-23rd-type-054a-frigate-into-east-sea-fleet |title=China commissions 23rd Type 054A frigate into East Sea Fleet |last1=Rahmat |first1=Ridzwan |date=30 December 2016 |website=IHS Jane's 360 |access-date=28 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170101001143/http://www.janes.com/article/66605/china-commissions-23rd-type-054a-frigate-into-east-sea-fleet |archive-date=1 January 2017 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|\u6ee8\u5dde/ ''Binzhou''<ref name=\"Rahmat_2016-12-30\"/>\n|\n|\n|29 December 2016<ref name=\"Rahmat_2016-12-30\"/>\n|East Sea Fleet<ref name=\"Rahmat_2016-12-30\"/>\n|Active<ref name=\"Rahmat_2016-12-30\"/>\n|-\n|530<ref name=\"oni_2015_PLAN_ID_Guide\">{{Cite report |author=United States Navy Office of Naval Intelligence |author-link=Office of Naval Intelligence |date=2015 |title=PLA Navy Identification Guide |url=http://www.oni.navy.mil/Intelligence_Community/china_media/posters/PLA_Navy_Identification_Guide.pdf |accessdate=6 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505000919/http://www.oni.navy.mil/Intelligence_Community/china_media/posters/PLA_Navy_Identification_Guide.pdf |archivedate=5 May 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|\u5f90\u5dde/ ''Xuzhou''<ref name=\"oni_2015_PLAN_ID_Guide\"/>\n|\n|\n|27 January 2008<ref name=\"pd_2008-01-29\">{{cite web |url=http://military.people.com.cn/GB/42963/53000/6836603.html |title=\"\u5f90\u5dde\u8230\"\u6b63\u5f0f\u547d\u540d\u5165\u5217 \u547d\u540d\u6388\u65d7\u4eea\u5f0f\u5728\u821f\u5c71\u4e3e\u884c |language=zh |date=29 January 2008 |website=[[People's Daily|People's Daily Online]] |publisher=\u5f90\u5dde\u65e5\u62a5 |access-date=12 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151223012633/http://military.people.com.cn/GB/42963/53000/6836603.html |archive-date=23 December 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|East Sea Fleet<ref name=\"pd_2008-01-29\"/>\n|Active<ref name=\"pd_2008-01-29\"/>\n|-\n|536<ref name=\"Tate_2017-06-26\">{{cite web |url=http://www.janes.com/article/71766/another-jiangkai-ii-class-frigate-enters-service-with-the-chinese-navy |title=Another Jiangkai II-class frigate enters service with the Chinese navy |last1=Tate |first1=Andrew |date=26 June 2017 |website=IHS Jane's 360 |access-date=2