Way, Ob-Ugrian Union, Society for the Survival and Socio-Economic Development of the Mansi People, Ugrian Association, Youth Public Organization, Yurga Restoration\n\n[[File:Flag of Yamal-Nenets Autonomous District.svg|22px|border]] [[Yamalia]]/[[Nenets Autonomous Okrug]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Nenets people|Nenets]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of Yamal-Nenets Autonomous District.svg|22px|border]] [[Yamalia|Yamalia/East Nenetsia]]\n** Advocacy group: [[Yamal for Future Generations (Association of the Indigenous People of Yamal-Nenets Autonomus Region)]]\n\n== Saudi Arabia ==\n{{More citations needed section|small=y|date=January 2020}}\n{{Main|Secession in Saudi Arabia}}\n{{See|Ahrar al-Najran|Qatif conflict}}\n\n===Summary===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:100%\"\n|-\n!width=75|Number\n!width=275|Land\n!width=125|Capital\n!width=100|Area\n!width=100|Population\n!width=125|Ethnic\n!width=300|Main Political Party\n|-\n| align=center|1 || ''' [[Najran Region|Najran]]''' || '''[[Najran]]''' || align=center|149,511  || align=center|550,000 || [[Arabs|Shia Arab]] || [[Ahrar al-Najran]]\n|-\n| align=center|2 || '''[[File:Flag of Upper Asir.svg|22px|border]] [[Asir]]''' || '''[[Abha]]''' || align=center|76,693 || align=center|2,250,000 || [[Arabs]] || Asser Regional Movement (ARM)\n|-\n| align=center|3 || '''[[File:Flag of the Emirate of Ha'il.svg|22px|border]] [[Ha'il Region|Jabal Shammar]]''' || '''[[Ha'il]]''' || align=center|103,887 || align=center|600,000 || [[Arabs]] || Shammar Revival Movement\n|-\n| align=center|4 || '''[[Eastern Province, Saudi Arabia|Al-Hassa]]''' || '''[[Dammam]]''' || align=center|672,522  || align=center|5,000,000 || [[Arabs|Shia Arab]] || \n|- style=\"background:silver;\"\n| align=\"center\" |'''Total'''||'''{{flagdeco|Saudi Arabia}} [[Saudi Arabia]]'''||'''[[Riyadh]]'''|| align=\"center\" |'''1,002,603'''|| align=\"center\" |'''8,400,000'''||'''[[Saudi Arabia]]'''||'''[[Saudi Arabia]]'''\n|}\n\n[[File:Arabia 1914.png|thumb|200px|The [[Arabian Peninsula]] in 1914.]]\n[[File:Ash_Sharqiyah_in_Saudi_Arabia.svg|thumb|200px|Map of Saudi Arabia with the Eastern Province highlighted.]]\n\nIn 2013 Robin Wright\u2019s colorful map of a politically re-divided Middle East in the New York Times, which illustrated her article \u201cImagining a Remapped Middle East.\u201d The map, entitled \u201cHow 5 Could Become 14,\u201d shows a hypothetical future division of Libya, Iraq, Syria, Yemen, and Saudi Arabia into 14 potential new countries along with two additional city-states. I was immediately reminded of Ralph Peters\u2019 troublesome remapping of the same region. As explained in a previous GeoCurrents post, Peters\u2019 intriguing mental exercise in redrawing national boundaries was widely misinterpreted across the Muslim world as indicating a nefarious plot to enhance US power. As a result, the region\u2019s pronounced anti-Americanism was further inflamed.<ref>http://www.geocurrents.info/geopolitics/myth-nation-state/robin-wrights-audacious-remapping-middle-east</ref><ref>https://moderndiplomacy.eu/2015/03/26/from-one-yemen-to-a-dissolution-of-saudi-arabia/</ref><ref>http://geocurrents.info/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Robin-Wrights-Remapped-Middle-East.png</ref><ref>http://geocurrents.info/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Saudi-Arabia-Remapped-by-Robin-Wright.png</ref>\n\nFurthermore, in June 2012 the Yemeni newspaper ''Al-Shareh'' revealed the names of high-ranking Yemeni state officials and tribal sheikhs who had been receiving monthly bribes from Saudi Arabia. This sparked anger among Yemenis, and a group of Yemeni activists founded the \"Asir Movement\" in order to reclaim the provinces of Asir, Najran, and Jizan, which Yemen conceded in the 2000 [[Treaty of Jeddah (2000)|Treaty of Jeddah]]. A \"[[Human rights|rights]] organization which has worked to denounce Saudi Arabia\u2019s abuses in northern Yemen\",<ref name=PressTV>{{cite news|title=Yemen's Houthis standing ground against Saudi Arabia |url= http://www.presstv.com/detail/2014/02/07/349604/houthis-stand-ground-against-s-arabia |work=Press TV| date=February 7, 2014}}</ref> the Asir Movement described itself as a \u201ccivil popular\u201d movement that seeks to raise \"internal Yemeni awareness\" about the situation and to explore legal remedies against Saudi Arabia \"for their involvement and assistance in abdicating Yemen\u2019s historical right to its territories\", all while emphasizing Yemeni unity. The movement sought to speak out against the 2000 Jeddah border agreement as well as the 1934 Taif Agreement that was signed in 1934 to end the [[Saudi\u2013Yemeni War]].<ref>{{cite news|author1=Jomana Farhat|title=Saudi-Yemeni Border: A Line in the Sand|url=http://english.al-akhbar.com/node/8500|work=Al Akhbar|date=June 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Qatif conflict]] refers to the modern phase of [[sectarian]] tensions and violence in Eastern Arabia between Arab Shi'a Muslims and Arab Sunni majority, which has ruled Saudi Arabia since early 20th century. The conflict encompasses civil unrest which has been sporadically ongoing since [[1979 Qatif Uprising|1979 events]], pro-democracy and pro-human rights [[2011\u201312 Saudi Arabian protests|protests]] and occasional armed incidents, which increased in 2017 as part of the [[2017\u201319 Qatif unrest]].\n\n[[Najran Region|Najran]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Arabs|Shia Arab]]\n** Proposed state: [[Najran Region|Najran]]\n** Militant organizations: [[Ismaili Defense Group]], [[Ahrar al-Najran]], [[Najran Valleys Liberation Organization]]\n** Organization: [[Najran Ismaili Association]]\n** Political party: [[Disobedience (political party)|Disobedience (Tamarrod)]], [[Najran Now]]\n\n[[File:Flag of Upper Asir.svg|22px|border]] [[Asir]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Arabs|Arab]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of Upper Asir.svg|22px|border]] [[Asir]]\n** Advocacy groups: [[Abha Asir Highland Organization]], [[Asser Regional Movement (ARM)]]\n** Movement: [[Asir Movement]], [[Idrisi Movement]]\n** Militant organization: [[Democratic Popular Front for the Liberation of the Pennisula]]\n** Organization: [[European Asir Organization]]\n\n[[File:Flag of the Emirate of Ha'il.svg|22px|border]] [[Emirate of Jabal Shammar|Jabal Shammar]] ([[Ha'il Region]])<ref>https://css.ethz.ch/content/dam/ethz/special-interest/gess/cis/center-for-securities-studies/resources/docs/ISPSW_506_Bodansky.pdf</ref>\n* Ethnic group: [[Arabs|Arab]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of the Emirate of Ha'il.svg|22px|border]] [[Emirate of Jabal Shammar|Jabal Shammar]]\n** Advocacy groups: [[Dhi Qar Shammar Tribal Union]], [[Jabal Shammar Exile Association]], [[Shamariyeh (organization)|Shamariyeh]]\n** Militant organization: [[Al-Sanadid Forces]]\n** Movements: [[Asir Movement]], [[Idrisi Movement]], [[Shammar Revival Movement]], [[Qajtanite Movement]]\n** Organization: [[Haiyel Shammar People's Organization]]\n** Political party: [[Shammar Nation]]\n\n[[Al-Ahsa Governorate|Al-Hassa]] ([[Eastern Province, Saudi Arabia]]) ([[Qatif conflict]])\n* Ethnic group: [[Arabs|Shia Arab]]\n** Proposed state: [[Al-Ahsa Governorate|Al-Hassa]]\n\n== Sri Lanka ==\n{{Main|Sri Lankan Civil War}}\n\n{{flag|Tamil Eelam}}\n* Ethnic group: [[Sri Lankan Tamil people|Tamil]]\n** Proposed state: [[Tamil Eelam]] or merge with [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]\n** Militant organisation: [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]] (Active, but militarily dormant since 2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.detnews.com/article/20090518/NATION/905180344/1020/Rebels-admit-defeat-in-Sri-Lankan-civil-war|title=Rebels admit defeat in Sri Lankan civil war &#124; detnews.com &#124; The Detroit News|publisher=detnews.com|accessdate=30 May 2009}}{{Dead link|date=June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/two-malaysian-dap-assemblymen-eight-others-charged-for-alleged-links-to-terror-group|title=Two Malaysian DAP assemblymen, 8 others charged over alleged links to Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam|date=29 October 2019|publisher=The Straits Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/10/28/twelve-allegedly-linked-to-ltte-to-be-charged-in-court-tuesday-oct-29|title=Twelve allegedly linked to LTTE to be charged in court|date=28 October 2019|publisher=The Star}}</ref>\n** Political party: [[Tamil National Alliance]]\n** Advocacy groups: [[Transnational Government of Tamil Eelam]]\n** Government in exile: [[Transnational Government of Tamil Eelam]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peacehall.com/news/gb/english/2005/04/200504211050.shtml |title=STATEMENT ON DECLARATION OF SHAN STATE INDEPENDENCE Boxun News |website=peacehall.com |access-date=20 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604194907/http://www.peacehall.com/news/gb/english/2005/04/200504211050.shtml |archive-date=4 June 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"tamllib\">{{cite web | url = http://www.sangam.org/2010/12/Tamil_Struggle_18.php | title = Sri Lankan Tamil Struggle \u2013 Chapter 18: The First Sinhalese- Tamil Rift | publisher = Ilankai Tamil Sangam | accessdate =19 January 2012 | work = T. Sabaratnam}}</ref>\n\n== Syria ==\n{{Main|Syrian Civil War}}\n{{Further|Sectarianism and minorities in the Syrian Civil War|Mandate for Syria and the Lebanon|Federalization of Syria}}\n\n[[File:French Mandate for Syria and the Lebanon map en.svg|thumb|Right|Map showing the states of the French Mandate from 1921 to 1922]]\n\n[[File:Ala kurd\u00ean rojava.svg|22px|border]] [[Rojava]]\n* Ethnic and ethno-religious group: [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]], [[Yazidis]]\n** De facto autonomous region: [[File:Ala kurd\u00ean rojava.svg|22px|border]] [[Rojava|Federation of Northern Syria \u2013 Rojava]]\n** Political party: [[Democratic Union Party (Syria)|Democratic Union Party]]\n** Militant organisation: [[People's Defence Units]]\n** Political Movement: [[Democratic Confederalism]], [[Democratic Socialism]], [[Feminism]], [[Ecosocialism]]\n\n;Proposed states:\n\n[[File:Flag of Druze.svg|22px|border]] [[As-Suwayda]]\n* Ethno-religious group: [[Druze]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of Druze.svg|22px|border]] [[Jabal Druze State|Druze Democratic Republic]]\n** Political parties: [[Progressive Socialist Party (Syria)]]\n** Militant organisations: [[Jaysh al-Muwahhideen]]\n\n[[File:ArameanFlag.png|22px|border]] [[Aram (biblical region)|Aram]] {{citation needed|date=July 2017}} {{original research inline|date=July 2017}}\n* Ethno-religious group: [[Terms for Syriac Christians#Arameans|Arameans]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:ArameanFlag.png|22px|border]] [[Aram (biblical region)|Aramaean Republic]]\n** Political parties: [[Aramean Democratic Organisation]]\n** Advocacy group: [[World Council of Arameans (Syriacs)]]\n\n{{flag|Assyria}}\n* Ethnic group: [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]]\n** Proposed state: {{flag|Assyria|name=Assyrian Democratic Republic}}\n** Political parties: [[Syriac Union Party (Syria)|Syriac Union Party]], [[Assyrian Democratic Organization]]\n** Militant organisations: [[Syriac Military Council]], [[Sutoro]]\n** Advocacy groups: [[Assyria Council of Europe]]\n\n[[File:Official Flag of Syrian Turkmen.jpg|22px|border]] [[Syrian Turkmen]]\n{{See also|Turkish involvement in the Syrian Civil War}}\n* Ethnic group: [[Syrian Turkmen]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Official Flag of Syrian Turkmen.jpg|22px|border]] Autonomous or free [[Syrian Turkmen|Bay\u0131rbucak]] and [[Aleppo governorate|Northern Aleppo]] (Western Turkmeneli) or [[Turkey]]\n** Political parties: [[Syrian Turkmen Assembly]] (official governing umbrella for [[Syrian Turkmen National Bloc]] and [[Syrian Democratic Turkmen Movement]])\n** Militant organizations: [[Syrian Turkmen Brigades]]\n\n== Taiwan (''de facto'' state) ==\n{{Main|Secession in China|Taiwan independence movement|Retrocession Day}}\n{{See also|Political status of Taiwan|Cross-Strait relations|Foreign relations of Taiwan}}\n'''The {{flagdeco|TWN}} [[Taiwan|Republic of China]] (Taiwan or ROC)''' is a state that has diplomatic relations with 14 [[Member states of the United Nations|United Nations member states]] (as well as the [[Holy See]], an [[United Nations General Assembly observers|observer]]).\n\n*{{flagdeco|TWN}}{{flagdeco|Taiwan Province}} [[Taiwan Province|'''Taiwan Province, Republic of China (Taiwan)''']] \u2014 \"Taiwan Province, Republic of China\" has been officially proclaimed and semi-administered by the [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)]] since 1945 (Taiwan was annexed by the Republic of China in 1945, [[Retrocession Day|having been recently seized]] from the [[Empire of Japan]]), having existed for around four years prior to the [[Chinese Civil War|establishment of the People's Republic of China]] in mainland China in 1949 and the subsequent exile of the Republic of China from mainland China [[Republic of China retreat to Taiwan|and retreat to Taiwan]] in 1949. However, this administrative division has never had the full power of a \"Taiwan Province\" since its territorial claim, from 1949 and onward, has always overlapped with the seat of the [[Government of the Republic of China|national government of the Republic of China (Taiwan)]] in [[Taipei]]. In the present day, six [[Administrative divisions of Taiwan|province-level subdivisions]] ([[Special municipality (Taiwan)|special municipalities]]) have been [[Secession|carved out of]] (seceded from) Taiwan Province (by the Taiwanese (ROC) government), and, therefore, Taiwan Province is ''de jure'' (under [[Law of Taiwan|Taiwanese (ROC) law]]) divided into seven distinct province-level subdivisions, including itself. These province-level subdivisions are {{flagdeco|Kaohsiung}} [[Kaohsiung]], {{flagdeco|New Taipei}} [[New Taipei City|New Taipei]], {{flagdeco|Taichung}} [[Taichung]], {{flagdeco|Tainan}} [[Tainan]], {{flagdeco|Taipei}} [[Taipei]], {{flagdeco|Taiwan Province}}{{flagdeco|Penghu County}} [[Taiwan Province|Taiwan]] (including [[Penghu]]), and {{flagdeco|Taoyuan}} [[Taoyuan, Taiwan|Taoyuan]], and they are accompanied by another province-level subdivision (nominally part of mainland China), {{flagdeco|Republic of China}}{{flagdeco|Kinmen}}{{flagdeco|Lienchiang County}} [[Fujian Province, Republic of China|Fujian (Fukien)]] (including [[Kinmen]] and [[Matsu Islands|Matsu]]).\n\n=== Indigenous Taiwanese autonomy movement ===\n{{See also|Taiwanese indigenous peoples|History of Taiwan|Prehistory of Taiwan}}\n\n* Ethnic group: [[Taiwanese indigenous peoples]] ([[Amis people|Amis]], [[Paiwan people|Paiwan]] etc.)\n**Proposed autonomous region: Indigenous Taiwanese communities in Eastern Taiwan\n***Movement: Indigenous Taiwanese autonomy movement\n***Political parties: [[Taiwan First Nations Party]]\n*** Advocacy groups: [[Council of Indigenous Peoples]]\n**Proposed autonomous region: Indigenous Taiwanese communities in Western Taiwan and Eastern Taiwan\n***Movement: Recognition of Indigenous Taiwanese plains peoples, Indigenous Taiwanese autonomy movement\n***Political parties: [[Taiwan First Nations Party]]\n***Advocacy groups: [[Council of Indigenous Peoples]]\n\n=== Taiwan independence movement ===\n{{Main|Taiwan independence movement}}\n{{See also|History of Taiwan|Taiwanese nationalism|Taiwanese identity}}{{flagdeco|TWN}} '''[[Taiwan|Republic of China (Taiwan)]] ('''{{flagdeco|Kaohsiung}} '''[[Kaohsiung]],''' {{flagdeco|New Taipei}} '''[[New Taipei City|New Taipei]],''' {{flagdeco|Taichung}} '''[[Taichung]],''' {{flagdeco|Tainan}} '''[[Tainan]],''' {{flagdeco|Taipei}} '''[[Taipei]],''' {{flagdeco|Taiwan Province}}{{flagdeco|Penghu County}} '''[[Taiwan Province|Taiwan]]-[[Penghu]],''' {{flagdeco|Taoyuan}} '''[[Taoyuan, Taiwan|Taoyuan]])'''\n{{See also|Administrative divisions of Taiwan|Geography of Taiwan|List of islands of Taiwan}}\n\n* Ethnic group: [[Taiwanese people]] ([[Hakka people#Taiwan|Hakka Taiwanese]], [[Hoklo Taiwanese]], [[Kinmen|Kinmenese people]], [[Taiwanese indigenous peoples]], [[Mainland Chinese#Mainlanders in Taiwan|Taiwanese Waishengren]])\n**Proposed state:  {{flagdeco|TWN}}[[File:Flag of World Taiwanese Congress.svg|22px|border]] [[Taiwan independence movement|Republic of Taiwan]]\n***Movement: [[Taiwan independence movement]], [[Taiwanese nationalism]]\n****Note: The [[Democratic Progressive Party]] (DPP) has been democratically elected to power in the Republic of China (Taiwan) four times; in [[2000 Taiwanese presidential election|2000 (until 2004)]], in [[2004 Taiwanese presidential election|2004 (until 2008)]], in [[2016 Taiwanese presidential election|2016 (until 2020)]], and in [[2020 Taiwanese presidential election|2020 (until 2024)]]. Although the DPP has been the nominal ruling party of the Republic of China throughout these four ruling terms, the DPP has been pushing a pro-Taiwan independence agenda, whether tacitly or overtly. Some representatives of the DPP, such as [[William Lai]], argue that Taiwan independence should not even be considered an \"independence movement\" but is rather the recognition of the reality of the current situation of the [[Republic of China on Taiwan]]. Many supporters of Taiwan independence believe that Taiwan, under the formal name of the \"Republic of China\", is already an independent country from China, under the formal name of the \"People's Republic of China\".\n***Political parties: [[Pan-Green Coalition]] ([[Democratic Progressive Party]], [[Taiwan Solidarity Union]], [[Taiwan Independence Party]]), [[New Power Party]], [[Taiwan Statebuilding Party]]\n***Advocacy groups: Keep Taiwan Free (Taiwanese organisation), [[World United Formosans for Independence]]\n***Claimed territories: Taiwan (Kaohsiung, New Taipei, Taichung, Tainan, Taipei, Taiwan-Penghu, Taoyuan)\n***Area of claimed territories: Roughly 36,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>\n***Population of claimed territories: Roughly 24,000,000 people\n{{flagdeco|Kinmen}}{{flagdeco|TWN}} '''[[Kinmen|Kinmen County, Republic of China (Taiwan)]] (Kinmen)''' \u2014 Independence movement{{See also|Kinmen|Taiwan independence movement#The issue of Kinmen (Quemoy) and Matsu (Lienchiang)}}\n\n* Ethnic group: Kinmenese people, [[Taiwanese people]]\n**Proposed unification with a proposed state: {{flagdeco|Kinmen}}{{flagdeco|TWN}}[[File:Flag of World Taiwanese Congress.svg|22px|border]] Kinmen County, Republic of Taiwan\n***Movement: Kinmen-Taiwan unification movement, [[Taiwan independence movement]], [[Taiwanese nationalism]]\n****Note: [[Kinmen]] is currently ruled by the [[Taiwan|Republic of China (Taiwan)]], so it and Taiwan are ''de facto'' already united. However, Kinmen's history is highly distinct from Taiwan's, and they've only really had a shared history since 1949, when the [[Republic of China retreat to Taiwan|Republic of China retreated to Taiwan]]. Furthermore, Kinmen's recent history has been largely shaped by military conflict between the ROC and the PRC and by the fact that [[Martial law in Taiwan|martial law]] was abolished in Kinmen in 1992, five years after it was abolished in Taiwan (in 1987). If the \"[[Taiwan independence movement|Republic of Taiwan]]\" were to be established, many people are uncertain of whether Kinmen should be included in this new country. Some young people in Kinmen identify as Taiwanese but the Kinmen County government is pushing a [[Chinese unification|pro-(re)unification]] (with the PRC) agenda.\n***Area of Kinmen: Roughly 150&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>\n***Population of Kinmen: Roughly 130,000 people\n\n=== Various Chinese (re)unification movements ===\n{{Main|Chinese unification|Greater China|Chinese Civil War}}\n{{See also|Two Chinas|1992 Consensus|Anti-Secession Law}}{{flagdeco|TWN}} '''[[Taiwan|Republic of China (Taiwan)]] ({{flagdeco|Kaohsiung}} KH, {{flagdeco|Kinmen}} Kinmen, {{flagdeco|Lienchiang County}} Matsu, {{flagdeco|New Taipei}} NT, {{flagdeco|Taichung}} TC, {{flagdeco|Tainan}} TN, {{flagdeco|Taipei}} TP, {{flagdeco|Taiwan Province}}TW-{{flagdeco|Penghu County}}PH, {{flagdeco|Taoyuan}}TY)''' \u2014 Irredentist movement\n{{See also|One-China policy|Taiwan Province, People's Republic of China|Taiwan, China}}\n\n* Ethnic group: [[Chinese people]], [[Taiwanese people]]\n**Proposed unification with a foreign state: {{flagdeco|CHN}}{{flagdeco|HKG}}{{flagdeco|MAC}}{{flagdeco|TWN}} [[Greater China]] ([[China]])\n***Movement: [[Chinese unification|Chinese (re)unification movement]], [[Chinese nationalism]]\n**** Note: This movement, [[Irredentism|irredentist]] in nature, is strongly pushed by the [[Government of China|Chinese (PRC) government]] and forms a [[One-China policy|core component]] of the country's [[Politics of China|national]] and [[Foreign relations of China|foreign policy]]. Around 2% of Taiwanese (ROC) society supports this movement.\n***Claimed territories: China (mainland), Hong Kong, Macau, Taiwan\n*** Area of claimed territories: Roughly 9,630,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>\n*** Population of claimed territories: Roughly 1,460,000,000 people\n\n'''{{flagdeco|Kinmen}}{{flagdeco|TWN}} [[Kinmen|Kinmen County, Republic of China (Taiwan)]] (Kinmen)''' \u2014 Irredentist movement\n\n{{See also|Kinmen|Special economic zones of China|Chinese unification}}\n\n* Ethnic group: Chinese people, [[Kinmen|Kinmenese people]]\n**Proposed unification with a foreign state alongside semi-autonomy: {{flagdeco|PRC}}{{flagdeco|Kinmen}}{{flagdeco|TWN}} Kinmen [[Special economic zones of China|Special Economic Zone]] of the People's Republic of China\n***Movement: Kinmen-China (re)unification movement, [[Chinese unification|Chinese (re)unification movement]], [[Chinese nationalism]]\n****Note: This movement, [[Irredentism|irredentist]] in nature, is strongly pushed by the [[Government of China|Chinese (PRC) government]]. Kinmen is viewed by the Chinese (PRC) government as a place where Chinese (re)unification experiments can be conducted, in preparation for the ultimate goal of annexing the [[Geography of Taiwan|island of Taiwan]]. The Kinmen County government has frequently clashed with the [[Mainland Affairs Council|Taiwan Mainland Affairs Council]] (which oversees relations with the PRC) over its willingness to allow the Chinese (PRC) government to infiltrate its society, economy, politics, cultural institutions, religious institutions, educational institutions, and local communities. It is unknown what percentage of Kinmenese society supports this movement but it is known that the Kinmen County government supports this movement and that it has been actively pushing for Kinmen's annexation into China (PRC).\n*** Area of Kinmen: Roughly 150&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>\n***Population of Kinmen: Roughly 130,000 people\n\n'''Chinese (re)unification under the ROC'''\n\n{{See also|Three Principles of the People|Project National Glory|Communist bandit}}\n\nThis is a variant of the Chinese (re)unification movement that advocates for the ROC to become the ruling regime of China again, replacing the PRC. Most members and supporters of the [[Pan-Blue Coalition]] in Taiwan, led by the [[Kuomintang|Chinese Nationalist Party (Kuomintang)]], support this movement, whether vaguely or strongly.\n\n* Note: Some proponents of this movement also advocate for the annexation (into China) of {{flagdeco|MNG}} [[Mongolia]] and other regions that were previously administered by the [[Qing dynasty]] (1644\u20131911), the Qing dynasty having been a [[History of China|historical regime of China]] preceding both the PRC and the ROC.\n\n'''Chinese (re)unification under a hypothetical \"New China\"'''\n\n{{See also|Chinese democracy movement|Chinese economic reform|Neoauthoritarianism (China)}}\n\nThis is another variant of the Chinese (re)unification movement. It advocates for the (re)unification of China (PRC) and Taiwan (ROC) under a hypothetical \"New China\". Proponents of this movement believe that both the PRC and the ROC have expired and that the only logical solution that is fair to both parties is to overthrow both regimes and replace them with a single \"New China\" regime that possesses characteristics of both the PRC and the ROC, as well as its own unique traits. Visions for such a \"New China\" range from a \"[[dictatorship]]\" to a \"[[democracy]]\". Vague support for this movement is widespread, but strong support for this movement is rare.\n\n== Tajikistan ==\n{{Main|Secession in Tajikistan}}\n\n[[Gorno-Badakhshan Autonomous Region|Badakhshan]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Pamiri people|Pamiri]]\n** Proposed state: [[United Badakhshan Peoples Republic]]<ref name=Badakhshon>{{cite web |url=http://www.geocities.com/Paris/9305/sheproot.html |title=Roots of the Conflict |publisher=El Gringo |accessdate=10 April 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091023215821/http://geocities.com/Paris/9305/sheproot.html |archivedate=23 October 2009}}</ref>\n** Political party: [[Lali Badakhshon]]<ref name=Badakhshon />\n\n== Thailand ==\n{{Main|South Thailand insurgency}}\n\n[[File:Pattani Flag.png|22px|border]] [[Patani (region)|Patani]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Thai Malays|Pattani Malays]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of Pattani.svg|22px|border]] [[Pattani Sultanate|Pattani Darul Makrif]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/para/pulo.htm |title=Pattani United Liberation Organization (PULO) |publisher=GlobalSecurity.org |accessdate=10 April 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090310155947/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/para/pulo.htm |archive-date=10 March 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>  unification with {{flag|Malaysia}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bm.cari.com.my/forum.php?mod=viewthread&tid=673099|title=Bendera Malaysia dinaikkan di selatan Thai|date=1 September 2012|website=cari.com.my|language=Malay}}</ref>\n** Militant organisation: [[Patani United Liberation Organisation]], [[Barisan Revolusi Nasional|Patani Malays National Revolutionary Front]], [[Runda Kumpulan Kecil]], [[Gerakan Mujahidin Islam Patani|Pattani Islamic Mujahideen Movement]], [[Islamic Liberation Front of Patani]]\n\n== Turkey ==\n{{See also|Minorities in Turkey}}\n{{Further|Human rights of Kurdish people in Turkey|Turkish nationalism|Turkish War of Independence|Greek genocide|Republic of Hatay|Western Armenia|Treaty of S\u00e8vres|Treaty of Lausanne}}\n\n[[File:Ethnolinguistic map of Turkey.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Ethnic Groups of Turkey.]]\n[[File:Kurdish majority Turkey-es.svg|thumb|right|300px|Map showing Kurdish majority areas within Turkey.]]\n\n[[File:Flag of Kurdistan.svg|22px|border]] [[Northern Kurdistan]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fas.org/irp/world/para/pkk.htm |title=Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK) |work=[[Federation of American Scientists]] |accessdate=23 July 2008 |date=21 May 2004 |first=John |last=Pike |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080428065853/http://www.fas.org/irp/world/para/pkk.htm |archive-date=28 April 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{Main|Kurdish nationalism|United Kurdistan|Kurdish Question|Kurdish Genocide}}\n* Ethnic group: [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of Kurdistan.svg|22px|border]] [[Kurdistan]]\n** Militant organisations: [[Kurdistan Workers Party]] (PKK), [[Group of Communities in Kurdistan]] (KCK), [[Kurdistan Freedom Hawks]] (TAK), [[Democrat Party of Kurdistan/North]] (PDK/Bakur), [[Revolutionary Party of Kurdistan]] (P\u015eK), [[Communist Party of Kurdistan]] (KKP)\n\n{{flag|Assyria}} {{Main|Assyrian nationalism|Assyrian struggle for independence|Assyrian genocide}}\n* Ethnic group: [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]]\n** Proposed state: {{flag|Assyria|name=Assyrian Democratic Republic}}\n** Political parties: [[Assyrian Democratic Movement]], [[Assyria Liberation Party]]\n** Militant organisations: [[Nineveh Plain Protection Units]], [[Dwekh Nawsha]]\n** Advocacy groups: [[Assyrian General Conference]], [[Assyria Council of Europe]]\n\n== Uzbekistan ==\n{{Main|Secession in Uzbekistan}}\n\n[[File:Flag of Karakalpakstan.svg|22px|border]] [[Karakalpakstan]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Karakalpaks]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of Karakalpakstan.svg|22px|border]] [[Republic of Karakalpakstan]]\n** Advocacy group: [[Free Karakalpakstan National Revival Party]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rferl.org/content/article/1079744.html |title=Uzbekistan: Shadowy Group Agitates For 'Free Karakalpakstan' |publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |date=5 April 2008 |accessdate=11 April 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217020232/http://www.rferl.org/content/Article/1079744.html |archive-date=17 February 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Vietnam ==\n{{Main|Secession in Vietnam}}\n\n[[File:Flag of KKF.svg|20px|]] [[Khmers Kampuchea-Krom Federation]]\n\n* Ethnic group: [[Khmer people]]\n\n[[Montagnard Foundation, Inc.]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Indigenous peoples of the Central Highlands in Vietnam]]\n\n== Yemen ==\n{{Main|Secession in Yemen}}\n{{See|Southern Movement|Greater Yemen}}\n\n[[File:Divided Yemen.svg|thumb|Yemen prior to unification|300px]]\n\n*[[File:Flag of South Yemen.svg|22px|border]] [[South Yemen]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of South Yemen.svg|22px|border]] [[South Arabia]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/8378727.stm |title=Five killed at secessionist protest in south Yemen |publisher=BBC |accessdate=25 November 2009 |date=25 November 2009 |location=London}}</ref>  {{flagicon image|Flag of the State of Aden.svg}} [[State of Aden]]\n** De facto state: [[Southern Transitional Council]]<ref name=\"alaraby\">{{cite web |url=https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/news/2017/5/16/gcc-aden-based-southern-transitional-council-doomed-to-fail |author=The New Arab |publisher=alaraby.co.uk |title=GCC: Aden-based Southern Transitional Council 'doomed to fail' |accessdate=8 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729134839/https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/news/2017/5/16/gcc-aden-based-southern-transitional-council-doomed-to-fail |archive-date=29 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"alaraby2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/News/2017/5/11/Governor-turned-president-Adens-Al-Zubaidi-announces-council-to-govern-South-Yemen |author=The New Arab |publisher=alaraby.co.uk |title=Banished Aden governor forms independent 'South Yemen' council |accessdate=8 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170511222357/https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/news/2017/5/11/governor-turned-president-adens-al-zubaidi-announces-council-to-govern-south-yemen |archive-date=11 May 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"aawsat\">{{cite web |url=https://english.aawsat.com/theaawsat/news-middle-east/thirty-southern-figures-reject-transitional-council-aden |author=Saudi Research & Marketing (uk) Ltd |work=Asharq Al-Awsat |title=Thirty Southern Figures Reject Transitional Council in Aden \u2013 ASHARQ AL-AWSAT English |accessdate=8 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517064844/http://english.aawsat.com/theaawsat/news-middle-east/thirty-southern-figures-reject-transitional-council-aden |archive-date=17 May 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*** Political party: [[South Yemen Movement]]\n*[[File:Flag of Hadhramaut.svg|22px|border]] [[Hadhramaut]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Arabs|Arab]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Kathiri flag.svg|22px|border]] [[Kathiri]], [[File:Flag of Quaiti Hadramaut.svg|22px|border]] [[Qu'aiti]], {{flagicon image|Flag of Wahidi Balhaf.svg}} [[Wahidi Balhaf]], {{flagicon image|Mahraflag.svg}} [[Mahra Sultanate|Mahra]]<ref name=\"geocurrents.info\">{{cite web |url=http://www.geocurrents.info/geopolitics/autonomous-zones/yemens-beleaguered-al-mahrah-seeks-autonomy |title=Yemen's Beleaguered Al Mahrah Seeks Autonomy |access-date=14 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714234058/http://www.geocurrents.info/geopolitics/autonomous-zones/yemens-beleaguered-al-mahrah-seeks-autonomy |archive-date=14 July 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.merip.org/mer/mer263/revolution-socotra |title=Revolution in Socotra \u2013 Middle East Research and Information Project |website=merip.org |access-date=12 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212180956/http://www.merip.org/mer/mer263/revolution-socotra |archive-date=12 February 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.yementimes.com/en/1716/intreview/2950/%E2%80%9CIt%E2%80%99s-a-political-sham-to-set-geographical-regions-based-on-vague-standards-without-any-legal-constitutional-or-political-authority%E2%80%9D.htm |title=Yemen Times [ Offline ] |website=yementimes.com |access-date=12 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212173836/http://www.yementimes.com/en/1716/intreview/2950/%E2%80%9CIt%E2%80%99s-a-political-sham-to-set-geographical-regions-based-on-vague-standards-without-any-legal-constitutional-or-political-authority%E2%80%9D.htm |archive-date=12 February 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n** De facto state: Hadhramaut Region, [[Protectorate of South Arabia]]\n*** Political party: [[File:Hadhrami League Flag.svg|22px|border]] [[Hadhrami League]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Lists of active separatist movements]]\n* [[List of historical separatist movements]]\n* [[Autonomous area]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Separatist movements per continent}}\n{{Secession in Countries}}\n{{Irredentism}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Active Separatist Movements in Asia, List Of}}\n[[Category:Asia-related lists|Separatist Movements, Active]]\n[[Category:Disputed territories in Asia|*Separatist Movements in Asia, Active]]\n[[Category:Lists of active separatist movements|Asia]]\n[[Category:Society-related lists|Separatist Movements in Asia, Active]]\n[[Category:Secessionist organizations in Asia| ]]\n[[Category:Myanmar-related lists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2019}}\nThis is a '''list of currently active [[Separatism|separatist]] movements in [[Asia]]'''. Separatism includes [[autonomism]] and [[secession]]ism. What is and is not considered an autonomist or secessionist movement is sometimes contentious. Entries on this list must meet three criteria:\n# They are active movements with current, active members.\n# They are seeking greater autonomy or self-determination for a geographic region (as opposed to personal autonomy).\n# They are the citizens/people of the conflicted area and doesn't come from other countries.\n\nUnder each region listed is one or more of the following:\n* ''De facto'' state: for regions with a ''[[de facto]]'' [[polity]]\n* Proposed state: proposed name for a seceding or anticipated [[sovereign state]]\n* Proposed autonomous area: for movements toward greater [[Autonomous area|autonomy for an area]] but not outright secession\n** ''De facto'' autonomous government: for governments with ''de facto'' autonomous control over a region\n** Government-in-exile: for a [[Government in exile|government based outside of the region in question]], with or without control\n** Political party (or parties): for [[Political party|political parties]] involved in a political system to push for autonomy or secession\n** Militant organisation(s): for [[irregular military|armed organisations]] or [[insurgency|insurgencies]]\n** Advocacy group(s): for [[Advocacy group|nonviolent, non-electoral, participatory entities]]\n** [[Ethnic]]/[[ethno-religious]]/[[racial]]/[[Regionalism (politics)|regional]]/[[Religious organization|religious]] group(s)\n{{TOC right}}\n\n== Azerbaijan ==\n{{Main|Nagorno-Karabakh War}}\n{{Further|List of active separatist movements in Europe}}\n\n;Breakaway state:\n\n{{Flag|Artsakh}}\n* Ethnic group: [[Armenians]]\n** De facto state: [[Republic of Artsakh]]\n** Government-in-exile: [[Azerbaijani Community of Nagorno-Karabakh]]\n\n== Bangladesh ==\n{{flagicon image|}} [[Bangabhumi]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Bengali Hindus]]\n** Region: South-western [[Bangladesh]]\n** Organisation: [[Banga Sena]]\n** Leader: Kalidas Baidya\n** Armed wing: Bir Banga\n\n{{flagicon image|Flag of Parbatya Chattagram Jana Samhati Samiti (PCJSS).png}} [[Chittagong Hill Tracts]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Jumma people]]\n** Political party: [[Parbatya Chattagram Jana Samhati Samiti|Parbotto Chottogram Jonshonghoti Shomiti]]\n* Further information: [[Chittagong Hill Tracts conflict]]\n\n{{flagicon image|}} [[Tripura]]\n** Ethnic group: [[Tripuri people|Tripuri]]\n** Organisation: [[All Tripura Tiger Force]]\n* Leader: [[Ranjit Debbarma]]\n\n{{flagicon image|Flag of Bnei Menashe.svg}} [[Zale'n-gam]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Kuki people]]\n** Region: Eastern borders of [[Bangladesh]] (primarily in parts of the [[Chittagong Hill Tracts]])\n** Organisation: [[Kuki National Organisation]]\n** Leaders: Pu S Haokip, Pu Letlam\n** Armed wing: [[Kuki National Army]]\n\n== China (Mainland China, Hong Kong, Macau) ==\n{{Main|Secession in China}}\n{{See also|Political status of Taiwan|One country, two systems|Ethnic minorities in China}}\n\n*'''The {{flagdeco|PRC}} [[People's Republic of China]] (China or PRC)''' is a state that is [[Foreign relations of China|recognised]] by 177 (out of 192 other) [[Member states of the United Nations|United Nations member states]] (as well as [[State of Palestine|Palestine]], an [[United Nations General Assembly observers|observer]]) as the [[China and the United Nations|sole legitimate government of China]]; the PRC represents China in the [[United Nations]] and is a [[Permanent members of the United Nations Security Council|permanent member of the United Nations Security Council]]. These states (that recognise the PRC's legitimacy) all recognise the [[Mainland|continental]] and island (e.g. [[Hainan]]) territory of \"[[mainland China]]\", which includes certain contentious regions such as [[Tibet]] and [[Xinjiang]], as being part of China (disregarding [[List of territorial disputes|border disputes]]). Mainland China does not include [[Hong Kong]], [[Macau]], and [[Taiwan]].\n**'''The''' {{flagdeco|PRC}} '''PRC's irredentist territorial claim to [[Taiwan]] as \"[[Taiwan Province, People's Republic of China]]\"''' \u2014 Many of the states that recognise the PRC's legitimacy have not clarified whether they specifically recognise China's [[Irredentism|irredentist]] [[Territorial dispute|territorial claim]] to the [[Geography of Taiwan|island of Taiwan]] and its [[List of islands of Taiwan|satellite islands]] (including [[Penghu]], [[Orchid Island]], [[Green Island, Taiwan|Green Island]], etc.), which it has [[History of Taiwan since 1945|never historically administered]]. China claims Taiwan as \"Taiwan Province, People's Republic of China\", but such a [[polity]] has never historically existed. Taiwan was designated a \"[[Provinces of China|province of China]]\" between 1887 and 1895 and a \"[[prefecture]] of [[Fujian|Fujian Province]]\" between 1684 and 1887, in both cases under the [[Qing dynasty]], an [[History of China|historical regime of China]] and the last Chinese [[Empire|imperial]] [[dynasty]]; the Qing dynasty [[Taiwanese indigenous peoples|never exercised absolute control]] over the entire island of Taiwan and its satellite islands.\n*'''The {{flagdeco|HKG}} [[Hong Kong|Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China]] (Hong Kong or Hong Kong SAR)''' is a highly autonomous territory whose sovereignty ultimately lies within China (PRC). Hong Kong's autonomy under a so-called [[One country, two systems|One Country Two Systems]] framework officially expires by 2047, at which point it is supposed to be fully integrated into China (PRC).\n*'''The {{flagdeco|MAC}} [[Macau|Macao (Macau) Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China]] (Macau/Macao or Macau/Macao SAR)''' is a highly autonomous territory whose sovereignty ultimately lies within China (PRC). Macau's autonomy under a so-called One Country Two Systems framework officially expires by 2049, at which point it is supposed to be fully integrated into China (PRC).\n\n===List of significant secessionist movements in China===\n* {{flagdeco|Taiwan}} [[Taiwan]] is not included in this list because it has never been governed by the [[China|People's Republic of China]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:100%\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"7\" bgcolor=\"#9acdff\" align=\"center\" |'''Significant Secessionist Movements in China'''\n|-\n! width=\"75\" |No.\n! width=\"225\" |Claimed Territory\n! width=\"100\" |Capital City\n! width=\"100\" |Area\n! width=\"100\" |Population\n! width=\"125\" |Ethnic Group\n! width=\"300\" |Primary Independence Movement\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |1 ||'''{{flagdeco|Tibet}} [[Tibet Autonomous Region|Xizang]] ([[Tibet]])'''||[[Lhasa]]|| align=\"center\" |2,500,000 || align=\"center\" |10,000,000 ||[[Tibetan people]]||[[Tibetan independence movement]]\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |2 ||'''{{flagdeco|East Turkestan}} [[Xinjiang]] ([[East Turkestan]])'''||[[\u00dcr\u00fcmqi]]|| align=\"center\" |1,700,000 || align=\"center\" |20,000,000 ||[[Uyghurs|Uyghur people]]||[[East Turkestan independence movement]]\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |3 ||'''[[File:Flag of the Inner Mongolian People's Party.svg|23px|border]] [[Inner Mongolia]]'''||[[Hohhot]]|| align=\"center\" |1,183,000 || align=\"center\" |25,000,000 ||[[Mongols in China|Chinese Mongols]]||[[Inner Mongolian independence movement]]\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |4 ||'''{{flagdeco|Hong Kong}} [[Hong Kong]]'''||[[Hong Kong]]|| align=\"center\" |1,110 || align=\"center\" |7,500,000 ||[[Hongkongers|Hong Kong people]]||[[Hong Kong independence|Hong Kong independence movement]]\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |5 ||'''{{flagdeco|Macau}} [[Macau]]'''||[[Macau]]|| align=\"center\" |115 || align=\"center\" |700,000 ||[[Macau people]]||[[Macau independence|Macau independence movement]]\n|- style=\"background:silver;\"\n| align=\"center\" |'''Total'''||'''{{flagdeco|China}} [[China]]'''||'''[[Beijing]]'''|| align=\"center\" |'''5,384,225'''|| align=\"center\" |'''63,000,000'''||'''[[Chinese people]]'''||'''[[Chinese nationalism]]'''\n|}\n\n=== List of fringe secessionist movements in China ===\n{{More citations needed section|small=y|date=January 2020}}\n* Claimed territories that do not exist are indicated in ''Italics''.\n* Claimed capital cities for non-existent territories are indicated in ''Italics''.\n* Independence movements for non-existent territories are indicated in ''Italics''.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:100%\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"7\" bgcolor=\"#9acdff\" align=\"center\" |'''Fringe Secessionist Movements in China'''\n|-\n! width=\"75\" |No.\n! width=\"225\" |Claimed Territory\n!Capital City\n! width=\"100\" |Area\n! width=\"100\" |Population\n! width=\"125\" |Ethnic Group\n! width=\"300\" |Primary Independence Movement\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |1 ||'''{{flagdeco|Manchukuo}} [[Northeast China|Dongbei]] ([[Manchuria]])'''\n|[[Harbin]] (Halbin)\n| align=\"center\" |787,000 || align=\"center\" | 112,000,000 ||[[Manchu people]]||[[Manchukuo Temporary Government]]\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |2 ||'''[[File:Flag of Yuyencia.png|23px|border]] [[Hebei]], [[Beijing]] and [[Tianjin]]'''\n|[[Harbin]] (Halbin)\n| align=\"center\" |113,000,000 || align=\"center\" | 118,000,000 ||Yuyencian people||[[Yuyencian regionalism]]\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |3 ||'''[[File:Flag of Basuria Independence Movement and the Republic of Basuria.png|23px|border]] [[Sichuan]] (Szechuan)'''\n|[[Chengdu]] (Chengtu)\n| align=\"center\" |485,000 || align=\"center\" |81,000,000 ||[[Sichuanese people]]||Bashu nationalism\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |4 ||'''[[Guangdong]] (Kwangtung)'''\n|[[Guangzhou]] (Canton)\n| align=\"center\" |179,800 || align=\"center\" |113,000,000 ||[[Cantonese people]]||Canton independence movement\n|-\n|- style=\"background:silver;\"\n|- style=\"background:#22B14C;\"\n|}\n\n[[File:Qing Empire circa 1820 EN.svg|thumb|Inner Mongolia and [[Outer Mongolia]] within the Qing dynasty, c. 1820]]\n\n=== Chinese provinces ===\n[[File:Flag of Basuria Independence Movement and the Republic of Basuria.png|23px]] [[Sichuan|Basuria]]\n\n* Ethnic group: [[Sichuanese people|Basurian]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of Basuria Independence Movement and the Republic of Basuria.png|23px]] [[Sichuan|Republic of Basuria]]<ref>https://fotw.info/flags/cn_sep.html</ref>\n***Movements: [[Basurian Revival Movement]], [[Basurian National Movement]]\n***Organizations: [[Free Basuria]]\n\n[[Guangdong]]\n\n* Ethnic group: [[Cantonese people]]\n** Proposed state:[[Guangdong|Republic of Cantonia]]\n** Movement: {{ill|Cantonese nationalism|lt=Guangdong independence movement|zh|\u5e7f\u4e1c\u72ec\u7acb\u8fd0\u52a8}}\n\n[[Manchuria]]\n{{Main|Manchurian nationalism}}\n\n* Ethnic group: [[Manchu people|Manchus]]\n** Proposed state: {{flagdeco|Manchukuo}} [[File:Flag of Fengtian clique.svg|22px|border]] [[Manchukuo]]\n*** Government-in-exile: [[Manchukuo Temporary Government]]\n*** Political parties: [[Northeast Administrative Committee]], [[Sulfan Manju|Free Manchuria (Sulfan Manju)]]\n*** Movement: [[Manchurian nationalism]]\n\n[[Shanghai]]\n\n* Ethnic group: [[Shanghainese people]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Proposed National Flag of Shanghai.jpg|23px|border]] Shanghai\n** Political party: Shanghai National Party (formed in New York)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://shanghainationalparty.com/\u7c21\u4ecb/|title=Shanghai National|website=Shanghai National Party}}</ref>\n\n[[Hebei]]\n\n* Ethnic group: Yuyencians\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of Yuyencia.png|23px|border]] Yuyencia\n** Proposed entity: Beijing, Tianjin, Hebei, parts of Liaoning, Chaoyang, Huludao, especially Chifeng\n** Movement: Yuyencian regionalism\n** Organizations: [[Yuyencia (organization)|Yuyencia]], Yuyencia National Foundation\n\n=== Chinese autonomous regions ===\n{{See also|Ethnic minorities in China|Autonomous regions of China|Autonomous administrative divisions of China}}\n'''There are five province-level autonomous regions within the People's Republic of China.'''\n\n'''[[Inner Mongolia|Inner Mongolia (Nei Mongol) Autonomous Region]] (Inner Mongolia AR)''' \u2014 Independence or Irredentist movement (Greater Mongolia){{Main|Inner Mongolian independence movement}}\n\n* Ethnic group: [[Mongols in China|Chinese Mongols]], [[Mongols]]\n**Proposed independent state: [[File:Flag of the Inner Mongolian People's Party.svg|22px|border]] Inner Mongolia or South Mongolia \n*** Movement: [[Inner Mongolian independence movement]]\n***Political parties: [[Inner Mongolian People's Party]] (member of the [[Unrepresented Nations and Peoples Organization]]), [[Southern Mongolian Democratic Alliance]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smhric.org/news_39.htm|title=\"Inner Mongolian People's Party\" and the basic facts about its key members|publisher=Southern Mongolian Human Rights Information Center|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225210314/http://www.smhric.org/news_39.htm|archive-date=25 February 2009|accessdate=11 April 2009}}</ref> [[Mongolian Liberal Union Party]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lupm.org/japanese/index.htm |script-title=ja:\u30e2\u30f3\u30b4\u30eb\u81ea\u7531\u9023\u76df\u515a|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100726004625/http://www.lupm.org/japanese/index.htm|archive-date=26 July 2010|accessdate=22 November 2010}}(JP)</ref>\n***Claimed territories: Inner Mongolia AR\n***Area of claimed territories: Roughly 1,200,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>\n***Population of claimed territories: Roughly 25&nbsp;million people\n**Proposed unification with foreign states: {{flagdeco|Altai Krai}}{{flagdeco|Altai Republic}}{{flagdeco|Buryatia}}[[File:Dzungaria flag .jpg|20x20px]][[File:Flag of the Inner Mongolian People's Party.svg|22px|border]]{{flagdeco|Mongolia}}{{flagdeco|Tuva}}{{flagdeco|Khakassia}}{{flagdeco|Kalmykia}}{{flagdeco|Ust-Orda Buryat Autonomous Okrug}}[[File:Flag of Agin-Buryatia.svg|22px]][[File:Flag of the Shor people.png|22px]] Greater Mongolia ([[Mongolia]])\n***Movement: [[Pan-Mongolism]]\n***Claimed territories: [[Altai Krai]] (Russia), [[Altai Republic]] (Russia), [[Buryatia|Buryatia Republic]] (Russia), [[Dzungaria|Dzungaria region]] (China), Inner Mongolia AR (China), Mongolia (country), [[Tuva|Tuva Republic]] (Russia), [[Khakassia|Khakas Republic]] (Russia), [[Kalmykia|Kalmyk Republic]] (Russia), [[Ust-Orda Buryat Autonomous Okrug|Ust Orda]] (Russia), [[Agin-Buryat Okrug|Agin-Buryatia]] (Russia), [[Gornaya Shoriya|Shoria]] (Russia)\n***Area of claimed territories: Roughly 4,500,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>\n***Population of claimed territories: Roughly 46&nbsp;million people\n\n[[Tibet Autonomous Region|'''Tibet (Xizang) Autonomous Region''']] '''(Tibet AR)''' \u2014 Independence movement\n{{Main|Tibetan independence movement}}\n\n* Ethnic group: [[Tibetan people|Tibetans]]\n** Proposed independent state: {{flagdeco|Tibet}} Tibet\n***Movement: [[Tibetan independence movement]]\n***Government-in-exile: [[Lobsang Sangay]], head of the [[Central Tibetan Administration]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dalailama.com/page.99.htm|title=Speech of His Holiness the Dalai Lama to the European Parliament, Strasbourg|date=14 October 2001|publisher=The Office of His Holiness the Dalai Lama|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325221348/http://www.dalailama.com/page.99.htm|archivedate=25 March 2009|accessdate=11 April 2009}}</ref> (member of the [[Unrepresented Nations and Peoples Organization]])\n*** Political parties: [[International Tibet Independence Movement]], [[National Democratic Party of Tibet]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rangzen.org/|title=INTERNATIONAL TIBET INDEPENDENCE MOVEMENT|publisher=International Tibet Independence Movement|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416141657/http://www.rangzen.org/|archive-date=16 April 2009|accessdate=11 April 2009}}</ref>\n*** Advocacy groups: [[Free Tibet]], [[Students for a Free Tibet]], [[Tibetan Youth Congress]], [[International Campaign for Tibet]]\n***Claimed territories: [[Tibet|Historical Tibet]], including Tibet AR (China), Qinghai Province (China), parts of surrounding Chinese provinces (especially Sichuan and Yunnan), and occasionally also Arunachal Pradesh (aka South Tibet; located within India)\n***Area of claimed territories: Roughly 2,500,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> (Arunachal Pradesh adds another roughly 84,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>)\n***Population of claimed territories: Roughly 10 to 15&nbsp;million people\n\n[[Xinjiang|'''Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region''']] '''(Xinjiang UAR)''' \u2014 Independence (East Turkestan) or Irredentist (Turkestan) or Islamic extremist movement\n{{Main|East Turkestan independence movement}}\n\n*Ethnic group: [[Uyghur people|Uyghurs]] and occasionally other [[Turkic peoples]]\n** Proposed independent state: {{flagdeco|East Turkestan}} [[East Turkestan]]\n*** Movement: [[East Turkestan independence movement]] and [[Uyghur nationalism]]\n***Government-in-exile: East Turkistan Government in Exile\n*** Advocacy groups: [[East Turkistan National Awakening Movement]], [[World Uyghur Congress]]\n***Claimed territories: Xinjiang UAR\n***Area of claimed territories: Roughly 1,700,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>\n***Population of claimed territories: Roughly 24&nbsp;million people\n**Proposed unification with foreign states: {{flagdeco|East Turkestan}}{{flagdeco|Kazakhstan}}{{flagdeco|Kyrgyzstan}}{{flagdeco|Turkmenistan}}{{flagdeco|Uzbekistan}} [[Turkestan]] (a contiguous Turkic region in Central Asia)\n***Movement: [[Pan-Turkism]]\n***Claimed territories: Xinjiang UAR + [[Kazakhstan]], [[Kyrgyzstan]], [[Turkmenistan]], and [[Uzbekistan]] countries\n***Area of claimed territories: Roughly 5,600,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>\n***Population of claimed territories: Roughly 88&nbsp;million people\n**Proposed Islamic extremist state: East Turkestan Islamic State\n***Militant organisations: [[Turkistan Islamic Party]]\n\n=== Chinese special administrative regions ===\n{{See also|Special administrative regions of China|One country, two systems|}}\n{{flagdeco|HKG}} [[Hong Kong|'''Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China''']] '''(Hong Kong SAR)'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/915237.shtml|title=HK 'Independence' party slammed, could cause trouble in the region|website=Global Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151126115310/http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/915237.shtml|archive-date=26 November 2015|accessdate=26 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/china/21652345-local-passion-flaring-chinas-fears-secessionism-are-overblown-determined|title=Determined|accessdate=26 November 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151209184059/http://www.economist.com/news/china/21652345-local-passion-flaring-chinas-fears-secessionism-are-overblown-determined|archive-date=9 December 2015|website=The Economist}}</ref> \u2014 Autonomist or Independence movement\n{{Main|Localism in Hong Kong|Hong Kong independence movement|Hong Kong autonomy movement}}'''Prominent autonomist and independence movements in Hong Kong SAR'''\n\n* Ethnic group: [[Hongkongers|Hong Kongese people]] ([[Demographics of Hong Kong|of various racial backgrounds]], mostly [[Han Chinese]])\n**Proposed independent state: {{flagdeco|HKG}} Hong Kong Independent City-State\n***Movement: [[Hong Kong independence|Hong Kong independence movement]], Hong Kong nationalism\n***Political parties: [[Localist groups (Hong Kong)|Independence-leaning localist groups]] including [[Hong Kong National Party]], [[Hong Kong Independence Party]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hkfront.org/index.html|title=Index|website=hkfront.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304035921/http://www.hkfront.org/index.html|archive-date=4 March 2016|access-date=27 December 2015}}</ref> and [[Youngspiration]]\n***Advocacy groups: [[Hong Konger Front]]\n***Protest/Riot groups: [[Hong Kong Indigenous]]\n***Claimed territories: Hong Kong SAR\n***Area of claimed territories: Roughly 1100&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>\n***Population of claimed territories: Roughly 7,500,000 people\n**Proposed autonomous region: {{flagdeco|CHN}}{{flagdeco|HKG}} Permanent Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China (no expiration date)\n***Movement: [[Hong Kong autonomy movement]]\n\n'''Sovereignty-related fringe movements in Hong Kong SAR'''\n\n* Ethnic group: [[Chinese people]], [[Hongkongers|Hong Kongese people]], [[Taiwanese people]]\n**Proposed unification with a foreign state: {{flagdeco|HKG}}{{flagdeco|TWN}} [[Hong Kong\u2013Taiwan relations|Union of the Free Chinese Republics]] (Hong Kong-Taiwan Union)\n***Movement: [[Chinese democracy movement]], [[Chinese nationalism]], Hong Kong nationalism, [[Taiwanese nationalism]]\n* Ethnic group: Chinese people, Hong Kongese people, [[Macanese people]], Taiwanese people\n** Proposed unification with foreign states: {{flagdeco|HKG}}{{flagdeco|Macau}}{{flagdeco|TWN}} Union of the Free Chinese Republics including Macau (Hong Kong-Macau-Taiwan Union)\n*** Movement: [[Chinese democracy movement]], Chinese nationalism, Hong Kong nationalism, Macanese nationalism, [[Taiwanese nationalism]]\n* Ethnic group: [[British people]], Hong Kongese people\n**Proposed unification with a foreign state: {{flagdeco|British Hong Kong}}{{flagdeco|GBR}} [[British Hong Kong]] (reversion of Hong Kong to British rule)\n***Movement: [[British Empire|British imperialism]], Hong Kong nationalism\n* Ethnic group: [[Americans]], Hong Kongese people\n**Proposed unification with a foreign state: {{flagdeco|HKG}}{{flagdeco|US}} [[51st state|American Hong Kong]] (admission of Hong Kong into the United States)\n***Movement: [[American imperialism]], Hong Kong nationalism\n* Ethnic group: Chinese people, Hong Kongese people, Macanese people, Taiwanese people\n**Proposed unification with a foreign state: {{flagdeco|CHN}}{{flagdeco|HKG}}{{flagdeco|Macau}}{{flagdeco|TWN}} Commonwealth of Chinese States ([[Greater China]])\n*** Movement: [[Chinese unification|Chinese (re)unification movement]], [[Chinese nationalism]]\n***Advocacy groups: [[Hong Kong Resurgence Order]]\n\n{{flagdeco|MAC}} '''[[Macau|Macao (Macau) Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China]] (Macau/Macao SAR)''' \u2014 Autonomist or Independence movement\n\n'''Prominent autonomist and independence movements in Macau SAR'''\n\n* Ethnic group: [[Macanese people]]\n** Proposed independent state: {{flagdeco|MAC}} Macau Independent City-State\n***Movement: [[Macau independence|Macau independence movement]]\n**Proposed autonomous region: {{flagdeco|CHN}}{{flagdeco|MAC}} Permanent Macao (Macau) Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China (no expiration date)\n***Movement: Macau autonomy movement\n\n'''Sovereignty-related fringe movements in Macau SAR'''\n\n* Ethnic group: [[Chinese people]], [[Hongkongers|Hong Kongese people]], Macanese people, [[Taiwanese people]]\n**Proposed unification with foreign states: {{flagdeco|HKG}}{{flagdeco|Macau}}{{flagdeco|TWN}} Union of the Free Chinese Republics including Macau (Hong Kong-Macau-Taiwan Union)\n***Movement: [[Chinese democracy movement]], [[Chinese nationalism]], Hong Kong nationalism, Macanese nationalism, [[Taiwanese nationalism]]\n\n== Cyprus ==\n{{Main|Turkish invasion of Cyprus}}\n\n;Breakaway state\n\n{{flag|Northern Cyprus}}\n* Ethnic group: [[Turkish Cypriot]]\n* Proposed: {{flagdeco|TRNC}} [[Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus]] ([[Foreign relations of Northern Cyprus#International recognition|Recognised by Turkey]])\n** ''De facto'' state: {{flagdeco|TRNC}} [[Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus]]\n*** Political organisation: [[Government of Northern Cyprus]]\n\n== Georgia ==\n{{Main|Occupied territories of Georgia}}\n\n''Breakaway states'':\n\n{{flag|Abkhazia}}\n\n* Ethnic group: [[Abkhaz people|Abkhaz]]\n** De facto state with [[International recognition of Abkhazia and South Ossetia|partial de jure recognition]]: {{flag|Republic of Abkhazia}}\n** Political organisation:[[Government of Abkhazia]]\n** Militant organization: [[Abkhazia Army]]\n\n{{flag|South Ossetia}}\n\n* Ethnic group: [[Ossetians]]\n** De facto state: [[Republic of South Ossetia]], proposed integration to {{flag|Russia}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rt.com/news/333069-south-ossetia-russia-referendum/|title=South Ossetia, former part of Georgia, to hold 'special' referendum to join Russia|date=20 February 2016|accessdate=9 March 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305010736/https://www.rt.com/news/333069-south-ossetia-russia-referendum/|archive-date=5 March 2016|publisher=RT}}</ref>\n** Political organisation: [[Government of South Ossetia]]\n** Militant organization: [[South Ossetia Army]]\n\n''Proposed autonomous movements'':{{When|date=March 2020}}\n[[Armenians in Samtskhe-Javakheti|Armenians in Javakheti]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Armenian people|Armenians]]\n** Proposed autonomous area: [[Javakheti|Javakhk]]\n** Advocacy groups: [[United Javakhk Democratic Alliance]], [[Virk(party)|Virk]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://times.am/2010/02/28/russia%E2%80%99s-javakhk-diaspora-demands-autonomous-region-status-for-samtskhe-javakhk/ |title=Russia's Javakhk Diaspora demands autonomous region status for Samtskhe-Javakhk |publisher=Times.am |accessdate=28 February 2010}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://asbarez.com/98039/us-state-department-and-javakhk-the-wikileaks-cables-part-i/ |title=US State Department and Javakhk: The WikiLeaks Cables Part I |publisher=Asbarez |accessdate=9 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011160744/http://asbarez.com/98039/us-state-department-and-javakhk-the-wikileaks-cables-part-i/ |archive-date=11 October 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=March 2020}}\n\n== India ==\n{{Main|Separatist movements of India}}\n{{Further|South Asian ethnic groups|Insurgency in Jammu and Kashmir|Insurgency in Punjab|Insurgency in Northeast India}}\n\n[[Assam]]\n{{main|Assamese nationalism}}\n* Proposed state: [[Assam]]\n** Ethnic group: [[Assamese people|Assamese]]\n** Military organization: [[File:Flag of United Liberation Front of Asom.svg|22px|border]] [[ULFA]]\n\n[[Bodoland]]\n{{main|Bodo nationalism}}\n* Proposed state: [[Bodoland]] \n** Ethnic group: [[Bodo people|Bodo]]\n** Militant organization: [[File:Front Nacional Democratic Bodoland.svg|22px|border]] [[NDFB]]\n\n[[Jammu & Kashmir]]\n* Proposed state: [[File:Jammu and Kashmir Flag (1952-2019).svg|22px|border]] [[Kashmir]] \n** Ethnic group: [[Kashmiris|Kashmiri]]\n** Political organization: [[All Parties Hurriyat Conference]], [[Jammu Kashmir Liberation Front]]\n** Militant organization: [[File:Flag of Lashkar-e-Taiba.svg|border|22px]] [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]], [[Hizbul Mujahideen]]\n\n[[Kamtapur]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ghosal |first1=Aniruddha |title=Former Militants of Banned Outfit Among Those on Election Duty in Darjeeling |url=https://www.news18.com/news/politics/former-militants-of-banned-outfit-among-those-on-election-duty-in-darjeeling-2105749.html |website=News18 |accessdate=15 October 2019|quote=The organisation, banned by the Union government in 2014, aims to carve out a separate Kamtapur nation from India, {{sic|comprising |hide=y|of}} six districts in West Bengal and four in Assam}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=BASUMATARY |first1=RINOY |title=KLO vows to launch armed liberation struggle against 'India' |url=https://nenow.in/north-east-news/klo-vows-to-launch-armed-liberation-struggle-against-india.html |website=NORTHEAST NOW |accessdate=15 October 2019|quote=That imperialist India is the main enemy of our national struggle. Independent Kamatapur shall comprise the entire Kamatapur in India.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Selvaraj6 |first1=A |title=Suspected member of Kamtapur militant group arrested in Chennai {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India |