histories, personal accounts, biographies)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090503114041/http://www.remuseum.org.uk/corpshistory/rem_corps_part16.htm#chindits Royal Engineers Museum] Engineers with the Chindits\n* [http://www.chindits.info/index.html The Chindits]\n* [http://history.amedd.army.mil/booksdocs/wwii/CrisisFleeting/bookfour.htm Office of the US Surgeon General: Office of Medical History: Book 4, With Wingate's Chindits] [https://web.archive.org/web/20041015212334/http://history.amedd.army.mil/booksdocs/wwii/CrisisFleeting/frameindex.html index]\n* [http://www.glanmore.org/gvf/jri1.html G. V. Faulkner, MD, MC. Medical Report on Operations, 77th Indian Infantry Brigade]\n* Chindit Special Force Burma 1944 http://www.chindit.net/\n* https://www.amazon.co.uk/Chindit-Special-Force-Burma-1944-ebook/dp/B079KHP6VG/ref=tmm_kin_swatch_0?_encoding=UTF8&qid=1571043073&sr=8-12\n\n{{Indian Divisions in World War II}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:3rd Division}}\n[[Category:Groups of World War II]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations of Burma in World War II]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1942]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations of India in World War II]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations of the British Empire in World War II]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1945]]\n", "name_user": "Eastfarthingan", "label": "safe", "comment": "infobox layout", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chindits"}
{"title_page": "Arnold Ventures LLC", "text_new": "{{COI|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name         = Arnold Ventures\n| logo         =\n| type         = [[Limited liability corporation]]\n| founder      = {{unbulleted list|[[John D. Arnold]]|Laura Arnold}}\n| founded_date =\n| key_people   = {{unbulleted list|[[John D. Arnold]]|Laura Arnold}}\n| homepage     = https://www.arnoldventures.org\n}}\n'''Arnold Ventures''' (formerly known as The '''Laura and John Arnold Foundation)''' brings \"philanthropy and political giving together in a new limited-liability corporation\"<ref name=\"insidephilanthropy.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidephilanthropy.com/home/2019/1/28/when-philanthropy-is-not-enough-a-top-billionaire-donor-couple-take-a-broader-approach-to-impact|title=When Philanthropy Is Not Enough: A Top Donor Couple Takes a Broader Approach to Impact|website=Inside Philanthropy|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> run by [[John D. Arnold]], a former [[Enron]] trader and American [[hedge fund]] manager, and his wife Laura Arnold.<ref name=Wired2017>{{cite news|last1=Apple|first1=Sam|title=The Young Billionaire Behind the War on Bad Science|url=https://www.wired.com/2017/01/john-arnold-waging-war-on-bad-science/|work=Wired|date=January 22, 2017}}</ref>  The organization was founded in 2008, the same year that the Arnolds signed the [[Giving Pledge]], a pledge by some [[high-net-worth individual]]s to donate a large fraction of their income to philanthropic causes during their lifetimes.<ref name=Philan2011>{{cite web|url=http://philanthropy.com/article/A-Thirtysomething-Billionaire/129397/|title = A Thirtysomething Billionaire Couple Take on Tough Issues Via Giving|date = October 16, 2011|last = Preston|first = Caroline|publisher = [[Chronicle of Philanthropy]]}}</ref>\n\nThe foundation has funded a wide range of interventions, many controversial, including Oregon's open primary ballot, Planned Parenthood, the Guttmacher Institute, the Network of Abortion Funds, the Center of Reproductive Rights,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.2ndvote.com/meet-the-arnolds/|title=Meet the Arnolds: Planned Parenthood's Billionaire Benefactors|date=2018-06-04|website=2ndVote|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> [[education reform]], efforts to end public pensions, a data-first approach to criminal justice, and improving [[Replication crisis|reproducibility]] and transparency in science through the funding of [[open science]] and [[metascience]].<ref name=Wired2017/>  The organization has also been described as \"another example of billionaire donors becoming ever more sophisticated about using private wealth to influence public policy\u2014wielding exponentially more power in American life than ordinary citizens of more modest means.\"<ref name=\"insidephilanthropy.com\"/>\n\n==History and controversy==\nArnold started donating to the [[Knowledge Is Power Program]] (KIPP) in 2004 with a gift of $30,000 which was then based in Houston, and two years later he and his wife pledged $10 million to help KIPP expand to other cities.<ref name=\"Philan2011\" />  Other multi-million gifts followed to other education programs, for example to [[Washington, D.C.]] city schools for [[merit pay]], to [[Teach for America]], and to [[StudentsFirst]].<ref name=\"Philan2011\" />\n\nSince 2008, the foundation has invested more than $1 billion in a variety of political initiatives, focusing on pensions, pretrial and criminal justice, prescription drug prices, the quality of academic research, combating predatory higher education practices, the evaluation of social programs, school system governance, and electoral reform. In the period 2011\u20132016, LJAF made $684 million in grants, distributed as follows: $75 million for criminal justice, $206 million for education, $147 million for evidence-based policy and innovation, $1.5 million for planning, $81 million for research integrity, $5 million for science and technology, $56 million for sustainable public finance, and $112 million for new initiatives.<ref name=\"grants\">{{cite web|url=http://www.arnoldfoundation.org/grants|title=Grants|publisher=Laura and John Arnold Foundation|accessdate=March 25, 2014}}</ref> In August 2012, the foundation launched the Giving Library to help other philanthropists make their gifts more efficient and effective.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/luisakroll/2012/08/14/billionaire-john-arnold-and-his-wife-launch-giving-library/ |title=Billionaire John Arnold And His Wife Launch Giving Library|first=Luisa|last=Kroll|work=Forbes |date=August 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThis data-driven approach has caused major controversies:\n\n*In 2013, LJAF starting making a web-based tool available to assist courts in better assessing whether to release people [[Bail in the United States|on bail]] or keep them imprisoned after they are arrested but before the trial begins.<ref name=\"ABA2013\" /> The foundation was sued by the families of two victims, the perpetrators of which were released due to this \"public safety assessment tool.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/dog-the-bounty-hunter-chris-christie_n_597f50f8e4b02a8434b80716|title=Dog The Bounty Hunter Joins Lawsuit Against Chris Christie Over Bail Reform|last=Wing|first=Nick|date=2017-07-31|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/solutions/2019/02/18/controversial-algorithms-help-decide-who-stays-jail-goes-free/2863797002/|title=Who stays in jail before trial? Who goes free? Sometimes, an algorithm helps decide|website=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> One released murderer had \"violated two probations. He was a convicted felon. And he had a gun charge just five days before the murder.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/08/18/543976003/did-a-bail-reform-algorithm-contribute-to-this-san-francisco-man-s-murder|title=Did A Bail Reform Algorithm Contribute To This San Francisco Man's Murder?|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> Despite this, the foundation \"plans to make the tool available nationwide via an undisclosed national technical systems provider.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidesources.com/arnold-foundation-to-roll-out-pretrial-risk-assessment-tool-nationwide/|title=Arnold Foundation to Roll Out Pretrial Risk Assessment Tool Nationwide|date=2018-09-04|website=InsideSources|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n*In 2016, the foundation funded continuous aerial surveillance of [[Baltimore|Baltimore]], Maryland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-08-25/baltimore-police-will-continue-aerial-surveillance-program|title=Baltimore Will Continue Aerial Surveillance Program|date=2016-08-25|website=Bloomberg.com}}</ref><ref name=\"radiolab surveillance\">{{cite web|url=http://www.radiolab.org/story/update-eye-sky/|title=Radiolab Podcast|date=2016-09-12}}</ref> ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'' reported that the foundation donated $360,000 to fund a controversial surveillance program in Baltimore that conducted secret, warrantless aerial surveillance of Baltimoreans on behalf of the Baltimore Police Department. The BPD conducted the surveillance without informing elected officials or the general public, suspending the program after public revelation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/crime/bs-md-ci-police-scandal-timeline-20180516-story.html|title=A look at recent Baltimore Police scandals, from De Sousa's resignation to Gun Trace Task Force|last1=Prudente|first1=Tim|website=The Baltimore Sun|publisher=The Baltimore Sun|accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/baltimore-city/bs-md-ci-laura-arnold-20160830-story.html|title=Donor to Baltimore police surveillance program says privacy debate 'healthy'|last1=Donovan|first1=Doug|website=The Baltimore Sun|publisher=The Baltimore Sun|accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n*In 2019, the Metropolitan Crime Commission released a report [https://metrocrime.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/Pretrial-Risk-Assessment-Scores-July-2018-March-2019.pdf] calling the \"public safety assessment tool\" a \"waste of money\" and concluded that the tool \"underrates the risk offenders pose to public safety.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fox8live.com/2019/07/01/crime-watchdog-new-orleans-risk-assessment-program-waste-money/|title=Crime Watchdog: New Orleans risk assessment program waste of money|last=Masson|first=Rob|website=www.fox8live.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>\nIn August 2019, Arnold Ventures recruited GOP operative [[Kevin Madden]] as head of advocacy. Madden is a former press secretary to disgraced House Majority Leader [[Tom DeLay]] and national spokesperson for both of [[Mitt Romney]]'s presidential campaigns\n\n==Areas of focus==\nThe Arnolds have used an [[investment management]] approach to giving, and as of 2013, the foundation targeted some of its giving to low risk, well-established institutions to help maintain their efforts and most of its giving to higher risk efforts that the Arnolds view as having a higher potential to drive change over the long term.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=The Bridgespan Group|url=http://givesmart.org/Give-Smart-Blog/February-2013/Laura-and-John-Arnold-Take-Risks-Make-Big-Bets.aspx|title = The Bold Philanthropy of Laura and John Arnold Embraces Risks and Bets Big|date = February 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Criminal justice===\nIn the period 2011\u20132016, LJAF allocated $75 million in grants for its criminal justice initiative.<ref name=grants/> An overview of criminal justice reform in the United States by [[GiveWell]] listed the Arnold Foundation as one of the top foundations in the United States working in the area, along with the [[Open Society Foundation]], [[The Pew Charitable Trusts]]{{'}} Public Safety Performance Project, the [[Ford Foundation]], [[Atlantic Philanthropies]], the [[Public Welfare Foundation]], and the [[Smith Richardson Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.givewell.org/labs/causes/criminal-justice-reform|title=Criminal Justice Reform|publisher=[[GiveWell]]|accessdate=May 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Anne Milgram]] worked as the [[Attorney General]] for the state of [[New Jersey]] where she worked to bring data to bear on the New Jersey state justice system and became a professor at [[New York University]]; she was recruited by the foundation to become its vice president for criminal justice.<ref name=ABA2013>{{cite news|last1=Davis|first1=Jenny B|title=Ex-NJ attorney general works to reform the pretrial process with a Texas foundation's backing|url=http://www.abajournal.com/magazine/article/ex-nj_attorney_general_works_to_reform_the_pretrial_process_with_a_texas_fo|work=ABA Journal|date=November 1, 2013|language=en}}</ref>  In a  2013 [[TED (conference)|TED talk]], she explained her work at LJAF creating tools to capture and use data to make the justice system more effective and efficient, which she called \"[[Moneyball]]ing crime\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ted.com/talks/anne_milgram_why_smart_statistics_are_the_key_to_fighting_crime|title = Why smart statistics are the key to fighting crime|last = Milgram|first = Anne|date = October 2013|publisher = [[TED (conference)|TED]]}}</ref> This was not well received. The Leadership Conference Education Fund had 120 criminal justice organizations sign a statement pushing for the halt of pretrial risk assessment instruments, stating \"although they may seem objective or neutral \u2013 threaten to further intensify unwarranted discrepancies in the justice system and to provide a misleading and undeserved imprimatur of impartiality for an institution that desperately needs fundamental change.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://civilrights.org/edfund/pretrial-risk-assessments/|title=Pretrial Risk Assessments|website=The Leadership Conference Education Fund|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n\nDespite this uncertainty, the foundation also funds the Data Collaborative for Justice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://datacollaborativeforjustice.org/about-us/funders/|title=Funding Agencies|website=Data Collaborative for Justice|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n\n===K-12 education===\nAccording to their list of grants, they have spent $206 million on grants related to education.<ref name=grants/> Including supporting<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/johnarnoldfndtn/status/966889016091058176?lang=en|title=I don\u2019t know the details of Mike Feinberg\u2019s departure from KIPP, but I do know that for the past 25 years there hasn\u2019t been a bigger champion or harder worker for education equality in America\u2019s underprivileged neighborhoods.|last=Arnold|first=John|date=2018-02-22|website=@johnarnoldfndtn|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> donating to a new fund led by the disgraced Mike Feinberg,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidesources.com/controversy-follows-funding-behind-kipp-co-founders-charter-school-venture/|title=Controversy Follows the Funding Behind KIPP Co-Founder's Charter School Venture|date=2018-07-29|website=InsideSources|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> founder of [[KIPP (organization)|KIPP]] after allegations of sexual abuse.\n\nIn May 2012, [[Reuters]] reported that the Laura and John Arnold Foundation had committed $20 million over a five-year period to an initiative called [[StudentsFirst]] led by [[Michelle Rhee]], who used to head the [[Washington D.C.]] public school system.<ref name=studentsfirst-1>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/05/15/michelle-rhee-education-a_n_1519720.html|title = Michelle Rhee, Education Activists Targeting U.S. Schools, Backed By Big Bucks|last = Simon|first = Stephanie|date = May 15, 2012|publisher = [[Huffington Post]] (originally from [[Reuters]])}}</ref> StudentsFirst reported its spending shortly thereafter.<ref name=studentsfirst-2>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/25/corrected-national-educat_n_1626053.html|title = StudentsFirst Spending: National Education Reform Group's Partial Tax Records Released|last = Simon|first = Stephanie|date = June 25, 2012|publisher = [[Huffington Post]] (originally from [[Reuters]])}}</ref>\n\nOn June 26, 2012, the Foundation launched the ERIN Project, a tool to help analyze the national K-12 education landscape<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/dallas/prnewswire/press_releases/Texas/2012/06/26/DC30943 |title=Laura and John Arnold Foundation Launches Powerful K-12 Education Tool|work=Dallas Business Journal|date=2012-06-26}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[United States federal government shutdown of 2013]], the foundation announced that it would be donating $10 million in emergency funds to the [[Head Start program]] so that some 7,000 kids from low-income families could continue to receive educational services.<ref name=Politico2013>{{cite news|last=Emma|first=Caitlin|title=Philanthropists pledge $10 million to restore 7,000 Head Start seats|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/10/philanthropists-pledge-10-million-nhsa-97939.html|newspaper=Politico|date=October 7, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-201_162-57606473/laura-and-john-arnold-donate-$10-million-to-help-head-start-amid-government-shutdown/ |title=Laura and John Arnold donate $10 million to help Head Start amid government shutdown |publisher=CBS News |date=2013-08-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/10/07/head-start-government-shutdown_n_4059584.html |title=Head Start Back In Business Thanks To Private Donation In Wake Of Government Shutdown |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date= 2013-10-07 |first=Jason |last=Cherkis}}</ref> The programs were at risk because their Federal grants were up for renewal after October 1.<ref name=Politico2013 /> The federal government reinstated Head Start funding in a deal approved by Congress on January 13, 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frias|first1=Jordan|title=Head Start Funding to Be Reinstated in Boston, Nationally|url=http://www.bostonurbannews.com/news/education/head-start-funding-to-be-reinstated-in-boston-nationally/|publisher=Boston Urban News|date=February 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\nLaura and John Arnold are listed as one of the biggest benefactors to the [[Wikimedia Foundation]].<ref>[https://15.wikipedia.org/contributors.html Wikipedia 15 Contributors] Retrieved January 15, 2016.</ref>\n\n===Public accountability===\nThe foundation has funded various politically-oriented [[501(c) organization#501.28c.29.284.29|501(c)4 organizations]], including Engage Rhode Island.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Juan|first1=Gonzalez|last2=Amy|first2=Goodman|title=Matt Taibbi on How Wall Street Hedge Funds Are Looting the Pension Funds of Public Workers|url=https://www.democracynow.org/2013/9/26/matt_taibbi_on_how_wall_street|work=Democracy Now!|date=September 26, 2013}}</ref>  Many of these organizations advocate pension fund reform, encourage state and local governments to reduce benefits to workers and to invest assets in riskier investments such as hedge funds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/looting-the-pension-funds-20130926 |title=Looting the Pension Funds: How Wall Street Robs Public Workers &#124; Politics News |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=2013-09-26}}</ref> Some have criticized the foundation's efforts, saying that hedge fund managers (like John Arnold) collect generous sums in fees for managing the funds, while the workers are left with reduced pensions.<ref name=Philan2011/><ref>{{cite news|last=Reid |first=Tim |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/06/25/usa-pensions-arnold-idUSL2N0F01Z820130625 |title=Texas hedge fund billionaire seeks California pension reform |publisher=Reuters |date= 2013-06-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.wpri.com/2013/05/20/a-closer-look-at-the-texas-billionaire-who-backed-engageri/ |title=A closer look at the Texas billionaire who backed EngageRI &#124; WPRI.com Blogs |publisher=Blogs.wpri.com |date=2013-05-20}}</ref>\n\nLJAF's attempts at pension reform have been met with hostility, and critics have argued that they have bought out groups such as the [[Pew Charitable Trust]], the [[Public Broadcasting Service]], and the [[Brookings Institution]].<ref name=huffpo-pew>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/24/pew-trusts-pensions_n_3983654.html|title = Promise Breakers: How Pew Trusts Is Helping to Gut Public Employee Pensions |last = Cohn|first = Gary|date = September 24, 2013|publisher = [[Huffington Post]] (originally from [[Frying Pan News]])}}</ref><ref name=sirota-1>{{cite web|url=http://pando.com/2014/02/13/how-pbs-is-becoming-the-plutocratic-broadcasting-service/|title = How PBS is becoming the Plutocratic Broadcasting Service|last = Sirota|first = David|date = February 13, 2014|publisher = [[PandoDaily]]}}</ref><ref name=sirota-2>{{cite web|url=http://pando.com/2014/02/12/the-wolf-of-sesame-street-revealing-the-secret-corruption-inside-pbss-news-division/|title = The Wolf of Sesame Street: Revealing the secret corruption inside PBS\u2019s news division|last = Sirota|first = David|date = February 12, 2014|publisher = [[PandoDaily]]}}</ref><ref name=latimes-brookings>{{cite web|url =http://www.latimes.com/business/hiltzik/la-fi-mh-brookings-20140228,0,2981449.story|title = First PBS, now Brookings: Has another institution sold its soul?|last = Hiltzik|first = Michael|date = February 28, 2014|publisher = [[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> LJAF has, in particular, generated controversy media coverage in connection with its funding of initiatives favoring pension reform.<ref name=\"huffpo-pew\" /><ref name=\"sirota-1\" /><ref name=\"sirota-2\" /><ref name=\"latimes-brookings\" /><ref name=\"pension-pew\" />\n\nIn March 2014, the ''[[Chronicle of Philanthropy]]'' reported that ''[[Pensions and Investments]]'' had asked the [[Pew Charitable Trust]] to stop taking money from the LJAF because of the LJAF's support for pension reform.<ref name=\"pension-pew\">{{cite web|url=http://philanthropy.com/blogs/philanthropytoday/pension-funds-press-pew-to-cut-arnold-foundation-ties/82149|title = Pension Funds Press Pew to Cut Arnold Foundation Ties|publisher = [[Chronicle of Philanthropy]]|date = March 4, 2014}}</ref> In July 2014, the Arnold Foundation donated $2.8 million to the [[Center for Public Integrity]] to launch a new project focused on state campaign finance. According to the ''[[International Business Times]]'', \"as CPI was negotiating the Arnold grant, [[John D. Arnold|Arnold\u2019s]] name was absent from a CPI report on pension politics.\" Arnold has spent at least $28 million on a campaign to roll back pension benefits for public workers.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sirota|first1=David|title=Enron Mogul John Arnold Funds State Politics... And Now Journalism About Money in State Politics|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/enron-mogul-john-arnold-funds-state-politics-now-journalism-about-money-state-politics-1650110|publisher=International Business Times|date=August 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Reid|first1=Tim|title=Texas hedge fund billionaire seeks California pension reform|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/06/25/usa-pensions-arnold-idUSL2N0F01Z820130625|agency=Reuters|date=2014-06-25}}</ref> Despite this spend,\u201cWhen people hear of an effort to get rid of pensions,\u201d says Bailey Childers of the National Public Pension Coalition (NPPC), which is supported by unions, \u201cthe source is almost always John Arnold.\u201d\n\n===Research integrity===\n{{see also|Metascience}}\nOne of the first projects funded by the foundation was research into [[obesity]], which was drawn to Arnold's attention when he heard an interview with [[Gary Taubes]] on the ''[[EconTalk]]'' podcast.<ref name=Wired2017/> Subsequent conversation between Arnold and Taubes led to the foundation funding the Nutrition Science Initiative in [[San Diego]], where Taubes and  [[Peter Attia]] and are trying to find the cause of obesity.<ref name=Wired2017/><ref>{{cite news|title=The money behind the fight over healthy eating |date=October 7, 2015|author1=Purdy, Chase  |author2=Bottemiller Evich, Helena|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/10/the-money-behind-the-fight-over-healthy-eating-214517|publisher=Politico}}</ref> The foundation backs the Action Now Initiative (ANI) which in turn funds The Nutrition Coalition (TNC) which backed [[Nina Teicholz]] when she wrote an investigative piece for [[The BMJ]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nutrition-coalition.org/site/?page_id=6|title=About Us|publisher=The Nutrition Coalition|accessdate=October 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 the foundation funded the launch of the [[Center for Open Science]] with a $5.25 million grant and by 2017 had provided an additional $10 million in funding.<ref name=Wired2017/>   It also funded the launch of the [[Meta-Research Innovation Center at Stanford]] at Stanford University run by [[John Ioannidis]] and Steven Goodman to study ways to improve scientific research.<ref name=Wired2017/>  It also provided funding for the [[AllTrials]] initiative led in part by [[Ben Goldacre]].<ref name=Wired2017/>\n\nLJAF has published guidelines, based on the [[open science|Open Science Framework]], that anybody seeking research funding from them must follow.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.arnoldfoundation.org/sites/default/files/pdf/Guidelines%20for%20Research%20Funded%20by%20LJAF%207-29-2013.pdf|title = Guidelines for Investments in Research|publisher = Laura and John Arnold Foundation|date = July 29, 2013|accessdate = March 25, 2014|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140326090912/http://www.arnoldfoundation.org/sites/default/files/pdf/Guidelines%20for%20Research%20Funded%20by%20LJAF%207-29-2013.pdf|archive-date = March 26, 2014|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2017 it had given around $80 million in grants under its \"Research Integrity\" initiative.<ref name=Wired2017/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website}}\n\n[[Category:Foundations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2008]]\n", "text_old": "{{COI|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name         = Arnold Ventures\n| logo         =\n| type         = [[Limited liability corporation]]\n| founder      = {{unbulleted list|[[John D. Arnold]]|Laura Arnold}}\n| founded_date =\n| key_people   = {{unbulleted list|[[John D. Arnold]]|Laura Arnold}}\n| homepage     = https://www.arnoldventures.org\n}}\n'''Arnold Ventures''' (formerly known as The '''Laura and John Arnold Foundation)''' brings \"philanthropy and political giving together in a new limited-liability corporation\"<ref name=\"insidephilanthropy.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidephilanthropy.com/home/2019/1/28/when-philanthropy-is-not-enough-a-top-billionaire-donor-couple-take-a-broader-approach-to-impact|title=When Philanthropy Is Not Enough: A Top Donor Couple Takes a Broader Approach to Impact|website=Inside Philanthropy|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> run by [[John D. Arnold]], a former [[Enron]] trader and American [[hedge fund]] manager, and his wife Laura Arnold.<ref name=Wired2017>{{cite news|last1=Apple|first1=Sam|title=The Young Billionaire Behind the War on Bad Science|url=https://www.wired.com/2017/01/john-arnold-waging-war-on-bad-science/|work=Wired|date=January 22, 2017}}</ref>  The organization was founded in 2008, the same year that the Arnolds signed the [[Giving Pledge]], a pledge by some [[high-net-worth individual]]s to donate a large fraction of their income to philanthropic causes during their lifetimes.<ref name=Philan2011>{{cite web|url=http://philanthropy.com/article/A-Thirtysomething-Billionaire/129397/|title = A Thirtysomething Billionaire Couple Take on Tough Issues Via Giving|date = October 16, 2011|last = Preston|first = Caroline|publisher = [[Chronicle of Philanthropy]]}}</ref>\n\nThe foundation has funded a wide range of interventions, many controversial, including Oregon's open primary ballot, Planned Parenthood, the Guttmacher Institute, the Network of Abortion Funds, the Center of Reproductive Rights,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.2ndvote.com/meet-the-arnolds/|title=Meet the Arnolds: Planned Parenthood's Billionaire Benefactors|date=2018-06-04|website=2ndVote|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> [[education reform]], efforts to end public pensions, a data-first approach to criminal justice, and improving [[Replication crisis|reproducibility]] and transparency in science through the funding of [[open science]] and [[metascience]].<ref name=Wired2017/>  The organization has also been described as \"another example of billionaire donors becoming ever more sophisticated about using private wealth to influence public policy\u2014wielding exponentially more power in American life than ordinary citizens of more modest means.\"<ref name=\"insidephilanthropy.com\"/>\n\n==History and controversy==\nArnold started donating to the [[Knowledge Is Power Program]] (KIPP) in 2004 with a gift of $30,000 which was then based in Houston, and two years later he and his wife pledged $10 million to help KIPP expand to other cities.<ref name=\"Philan2011\" />  Other multi-million gifts followed to other education programs, for example to [[Washington, D.C.]] city schools for [[merit pay]], to [[Teach for America]], and to [[StudentsFirst]].<ref name=\"Philan2011\" />\n\nSince 2008, the foundation has invested more than $1 billion in a variety of political initiatives, focusing on pensions, pretrial and criminal justice, prescription drug prices, the quality of academic research, combating predatory higher education practices, the evaluation of social programs, school system governance, and electoral reform   In the period 2011\u20132016, LJAF made $684 million in grants, distributed as follows: $75 million for criminal justice, $206 million for education, $147 million for evidence-based policy and innovation, $1.5 million for planning, $81 million for research integrity, $5 million for science and technology, $56 million for sustainable public finance, and $112 million for new initiatives.<ref name=\"grants\">{{cite web|url=http://www.arnoldfoundation.org/grants|title=Grants|publisher=Laura and John Arnold Foundation|accessdate=March 25, 2014}}</ref> In August 2012 the Foundation launched the Giving Library to help other philanthropists make their gifts more efficient and effective.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/luisakroll/2012/08/14/billionaire-john-arnold-and-his-wife-launch-giving-library/ |title=Billionaire John Arnold And His Wife Launch Giving Library|first=Luisa|last=Kroll|work=Forbes |date=August 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThis data-driven approach has caused major controversies:\n\n*In 2013 the LFAF starting making available a web-based tool to assist courts in better assessing whether to release people [[Bail in the United States|on bail]] or keep them imprisoned after they are arrested but before the trial begins.<ref name=\"ABA2013\" /> The foundation was sued by the families of two victims, the perpetrators of which were released due to this \"public safety assessment tool.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/dog-the-bounty-hunter-chris-christie_n_597f50f8e4b02a8434b80716|title=Dog The Bounty Hunter Joins Lawsuit Against Chris Christie Over Bail Reform|last=Wing|first=Nick|date=2017-07-31|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/solutions/2019/02/18/controversial-algorithms-help-decide-who-stays-jail-goes-free/2863797002/|title=Who stays in jail before trial? Who goes free? Sometimes, an algorithm helps decide|website=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> One released murderer had \"violated two probations. He was a convicted felon. And he had a gun charge just five days before the murder.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/08/18/543976003/did-a-bail-reform-algorithm-contribute-to-this-san-francisco-man-s-murder|title=Did A Bail Reform Algorithm Contribute To This San Francisco Man's Murder?|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> Despite this the foundation \"plans to make the tool available nationwide via an undisclosed national technical systems provider.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidesources.com/arnold-foundation-to-roll-out-pretrial-risk-assessment-tool-nationwide/|title=Arnold Foundation to Roll Out Pretrial Risk Assessment Tool Nationwide|date=2018-09-04|website=InsideSources|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n*In 2016, the foundation funded continuous aerial surveillance of [[Baltimore|Baltimore]], Maryland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-08-25/baltimore-police-will-continue-aerial-surveillance-program|title=Baltimore Will Continue Aerial Surveillance Program|date=2016-08-25|website=Bloomberg.com}}</ref><ref name=\"radiolab surveillance\">{{cite web|url=http://www.radiolab.org/story/update-eye-sky/|title=Radiolab Podcast|date=2016-09-12}}</ref> ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'' reported that the foundation donated $360,000 to fund a controversial surveillance program in Baltimore conducted secret, warrantless aerial surveillance of Baltimoreans on behalf of the Baltimore Police Department. The BPD conducted the surveillance without informing elected officials or the general public, suspending the program after public revelation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/crime/bs-md-ci-police-scandal-timeline-20180516-story.html|title=A look at recent Baltimore Police scandals, from De Sousa's resignation to Gun Trace Task Force|last1=Prudente|first1=Tim|website=The Baltimore Sun|publisher=The Baltimore Sun|accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/baltimore-city/bs-md-ci-laura-arnold-20160830-story.html|title=Donor to Baltimore police surveillance program says privacy debate 'healthy'|last1=Donovan|first1=Doug|website=The Baltimore Sun|publisher=The Baltimore Sun|accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n*In 2019, the Metropolitan Crime Commission released a report [https://metrocrime.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/Pretrial-Risk-Assessment-Scores-July-2018-March-2019.pdf] calling the \"public safety assessment tool\" a \"waste of money\" and concludes that the tool \"underrates the risk offenders pose to public safety\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fox8live.com/2019/07/01/crime-watchdog-new-orleans-risk-assessment-program-waste-money/|title=Crime Watchdog: New Orleans risk assessment program waste of money|last=Masson|first=Rob|website=www.fox8live.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>\nIn August 2019, Arnold Ventures recruited GOP operative [[Kevin Madden]] as head of advocacy. Madden is a former press secretary to disgraced House Majority Leader [[Tom DeLay]] and national spokesperson for both of [[Mitt Romney]]'s presidential campaigns\n\n==Areas of focus==\nThe Arnolds have used an [[investment management]] approach to giving, and as of 2013 the foundation targeted some of its giving to low risk, well-established institutions to help maintain their efforts, and most of its giving to higher risk efforts that the Arnolds view as having a higher potential to drive change over the long term.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=The Bridgespan Group|url=http://givesmart.org/Give-Smart-Blog/February-2013/Laura-and-John-Arnold-Take-Risks-Make-Big-Bets.aspx|title = The Bold Philanthropy of Laura and John Arnold Embraces Risks and Bets Big|date = February 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Criminal justice===\nIn the period 2011\u20132016, LJAF allocated $75 million in grants for its criminal justice initiative.<ref name=grants/> An overview of criminal justice reform in the United States by [[GiveWell]] listed the Arnold Foundation as one of the top foundations in the United States working in the area, along with the [[Open Society Foundation]], [[The Pew Charitable Trusts]]{{'}} Public Safety Performance Project, the [[Ford Foundation]], [[Atlantic Philanthropies]], the [[Public Welfare Foundation]], and the [[Smith Richardson Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.givewell.org/labs/causes/criminal-justice-reform|title=Criminal Justice Reform|publisher=[[GiveWell]]|accessdate=May 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Anne Milgram]] worked as the [[Attorney General]] for the state of [[New Jersey]] where she worked to bring data to bear on the New Jersey state justice system and became a professor at [[New York University]]; she was recruited by the foundation to become its vice president for criminal justice.<ref name=ABA2013>{{cite news|last1=Davis|first1=Jenny B|title=Ex-NJ attorney general works to reform the pretrial process with a Texas foundation's backing|url=http://www.abajournal.com/magazine/article/ex-nj_attorney_general_works_to_reform_the_pretrial_process_with_a_texas_fo|work=ABA Journal|date=November 1, 2013|language=en}}</ref>  In a  2013 [[TED (conference)|TED talk]], she explained her work at LJAF creating tools to capture and use data to make the justice system more effective and efficient, which she called \"[[Moneyball]]ing crime\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ted.com/talks/anne_milgram_why_smart_statistics_are_the_key_to_fighting_crime|title = Why smart statistics are the key to fighting crime|last = Milgram|first = Anne|date = October 2013|publisher = [[TED (conference)|TED]]}}</ref> This was not well received. The Leadership Conference Education Fund had 120 criminal justice organizations sign a statement pushing for the halt of pretrial risk assessment instruments, stating \"although they may seem objective or neutral \u2013 threaten to further intensify unwarranted discrepancies in the justice system and to provide a misleading and undeserved imprimatur of impartiality for an institution that desperately needs fundamental change.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://civilrights.org/edfund/pretrial-risk-assessments/|title=Pretrial Risk Assessments|website=The Leadership Conference Education Fund|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n\nDespite this uncertainty, the foundation also funds the Data Collaborative for Justice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://datacollaborativeforjustice.org/about-us/funders/|title=Funding Agencies|website=Data Collaborative for Justice|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n\n===K-12 education===\nAccording to their list of grants, they have spent $206 million on grants related to education.<ref name=grants/> Including supporting<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/johnarnoldfndtn/status/966889016091058176?lang=en|title=I don\u2019t know the details of Mike Feinberg\u2019s departure from KIPP, but I do know that for the past 25 years there hasn\u2019t been a bigger champion or harder worker for education equality in America\u2019s underprivileged neighborhoods.|last=Arnold|first=John|date=2018-02-22|website=@johnarnoldfndtn|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> donating to a new fund led by the disgraced Mike Feinberg,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidesources.com/controversy-follows-funding-behind-kipp-co-founders-charter-school-venture/|title=Controversy Follows the Funding Behind KIPP Co-Founder's Charter School Venture|date=2018-07-29|website=InsideSources|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> founder of [[KIPP (organization)|KIPP]] after allegations of sexual abuse.\n\nIn May 2012, [[Reuters]] reported that the Laura and John Arnold Foundation had committed $20 million over a five-year period to an initiative called [[StudentsFirst]] led by [[Michelle Rhee]], who used to head the [[Washington D.C.]] public school system.<ref name=studentsfirst-1>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/05/15/michelle-rhee-education-a_n_1519720.html|title = Michelle Rhee, Education Activists Targeting U.S. Schools, Backed By Big Bucks|last = Simon|first = Stephanie|date = May 15, 2012|publisher = [[Huffington Post]] (originally from [[Reuters]])}}</ref> StudentsFirst reported its spending shortly thereafter.<ref name=studentsfirst-2>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/25/corrected-national-educat_n_1626053.html|title = StudentsFirst Spending: National Education Reform Group's Partial Tax Records Released|last = Simon|first = Stephanie|date = June 25, 2012|publisher = [[Huffington Post]] (originally from [[Reuters]])}}</ref>\n\nOn June 26, 2012, the Foundation launched the ERIN Project, a tool to help analyze the national K-12 education landscape<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/dallas/prnewswire/press_releases/Texas/2012/06/26/DC30943 |title=Laura and John Arnold Foundation Launches Powerful K-12 Education Tool|work=Dallas Business Journal|date=2012-06-26}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[United States federal government shutdown of 2013]], the foundation announced that it would be donating $10 million in emergency funds to the [[Head Start program]] so that some 7,000 kids from low-income families could continue to receive educational services.<ref name=Politico2013>{{cite news|last=Emma|first=Caitlin|title=Philanthropists pledge $10 million to restore 7,000 Head Start seats|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/10/philanthropists-pledge-10-million-nhsa-97939.html|newspaper=Politico|date=October 7, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-201_162-57606473/laura-and-john-arnold-donate-$10-million-to-help-head-start-amid-government-shutdown/ |title=Laura and John Arnold donate $10 million to help Head Start amid government shutdown |publisher=CBS News |date=2013-08-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/10/07/head-start-government-shutdown_n_4059584.html |title=Head Start Back In Business Thanks To Private Donation In Wake Of Government Shutdown |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date= 2013-10-07 |first=Jason |last=Cherkis}}</ref> The programs were at risk because their Federal grants were up for renewal after October 1.<ref name=Politico2013 /> The federal government reinstated Head Start funding in a deal approved by Congress on January 13, 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frias|first1=Jordan|title=Head Start Funding to Be Reinstated in Boston, Nationally|url=http://www.bostonurbannews.com/news/education/head-start-funding-to-be-reinstated-in-boston-nationally/|publisher=Boston Urban News|date=February 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\nLaura and John Arnold are listed as one of the biggest benefactors to the [[Wikimedia Foundation]].<ref>[https://15.wikipedia.org/contributors.html Wikipedia 15 Contributors] Retrieved January 15, 2016.</ref>\n\n===Public accountability===\nThe foundation has funded various politically-oriented [[501(c) organization#501.28c.29.284.29|501(c)4 organizations]], including Engage Rhode Island.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Juan|first1=Gonzalez|last2=Amy|first2=Goodman|title=Matt Taibbi on How Wall Street Hedge Funds Are Looting the Pension Funds of Public Workers|url=https://www.democracynow.org/2013/9/26/matt_taibbi_on_how_wall_street|work=Democracy Now!|date=September 26, 2013}}</ref>  Many of these organizations advocate pension fund reform, encourage state and local governments to reduce benefits to workers and to invest assets in riskier investments such as hedge funds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/looting-the-pension-funds-20130926 |title=Looting the Pension Funds: How Wall Street Robs Public Workers &#124; Politics News |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=2013-09-26}}</ref> Some have criticized the foundation's efforts, saying that hedge fund managers (like John Arnold) collect generous sums in fees for managing the funds, while the workers are left with reduced pensions.<ref name=Philan2011/><ref>{{cite news|last=Reid |first=Tim |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/06/25/usa-pensions-arnold-idUSL2N0F01Z820130625 |title=Texas hedge fund billionaire seeks California pension reform |publisher=Reuters |date= 2013-06-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.wpri.com/2013/05/20/a-closer-look-at-the-texas-billionaire-who-backed-engageri/ |title=A closer look at the Texas billionaire who backed EngageRI &#124; WPRI.com Blogs |publisher=Blogs.wpri.com |date=2013-05-20}}</ref>\n\nLJAF's attempts at pension reform have been met with hostility, and critics have argued that they have bought out groups such as the [[Pew Charitable Trust]], the [[Public Broadcasting Service]], and the [[Brookings Institution]].<ref name=huffpo-pew>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/24/pew-trusts-pensions_n_3983654.html|title = Promise Breakers: How Pew Trusts Is Helping to Gut Public Employee Pensions |last = Cohn|first = Gary|date = September 24, 2013|publisher = [[Huffington Post]] (originally from [[Frying Pan News]])}}</ref><ref name=sirota-1>{{cite web|url=http://pando.com/2014/02/13/how-pbs-is-becoming-the-plutocratic-broadcasting-service/|title = How PBS is becoming the Plutocratic Broadcasting Service|last = Sirota|first = David|date = February 13, 2014|publisher = [[PandoDaily]]}}</ref><ref name=sirota-2>{{cite web|url=http://pando.com/2014/02/12/the-wolf-of-sesame-street-revealing-the-secret-corruption-inside-pbss-news-division/|title = The Wolf of Sesame Street: Revealing the secret corruption inside PBS\u2019s news division|last = Sirota|first = David|date = February 12, 2014|publisher = [[PandoDaily]]}}</ref><ref name=latimes-brookings>{{cite web|url =http://www.latimes.com/business/hiltzik/la-fi-mh-brookings-20140228,0,2981449.story|title = First PBS, now Brookings: Has another institution sold its soul?|last = Hiltzik|first = Michael|date = February 28, 2014|publisher = [[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> LJAF has, in particular, generated controversy media coverage in connection with its funding of initiatives favoring pension reform.<ref name=\"huffpo-pew\" /><ref name=\"sirota-1\" /><ref name=\"sirota-2\" /><ref name=\"latimes-brookings\" /><ref name=\"pension-pew\" />\n\nIn March 2014, the ''[[Chronicle of Philanthropy]]'' reported that ''[[Pensions and Investments]]'' had asked the [[Pew Charitable Trust]] to stop taking money from the LJAF because of the LJAF's support for pension reform.<ref name=\"pension-pew\">{{cite web|url=http://philanthropy.com/blogs/philanthropytoday/pension-funds-press-pew-to-cut-arnold-foundation-ties/82149|title = Pension Funds Press Pew to Cut Arnold Foundation Ties|publisher = [[Chronicle of Philanthropy]]|date = March 4, 2014}}</ref> In July 2014, the Arnold Foundation donated $2.8 million to the [[Center for Public Integrity]] to launch a new project focused on state campaign finance. According to the ''[[International Business Times]]'', \"as CPI was negotiating the Arnold grant, [[John D. Arnold|Arnold\u2019s]] name was absent from a CPI report on pension politics.\" Arnold has spent at least $28 million on a campaign to roll back pension benefits for public workers.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sirota|first1=David|title=Enron Mogul John Arnold Funds State Politics... And Now Journalism About Money in State Politics|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/enron-mogul-john-arnold-funds-state-politics-now-journalism-about-money-state-politics-1650110|publisher=International Business Times|date=August 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Reid|first1=Tim|title=Texas hedge fund billionaire seeks California pension reform|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/06/25/usa-pensions-arnold-idUSL2N0F01Z820130625|agency=Reuters|date=2014-06-25}}</ref> Despite this spend,\u201cWhen people hear of an effort to get rid of pensions,\u201d says Bailey Childers of the National Public Pension Coalition (NPPC), which is supported by unions, \u201cthe source is almost always John Arnold.\u201d\n\n===Research integrity===\n{{see also|Metascience}}\nOne of the first projects funded by the foundation was research into [[obesity]], which was drawn to Arnold's attention when he heard an interview with [[Gary Taubes]] on the ''[[EconTalk]]'' podcast.<ref name=Wired2017/> Subsequent conversation between Arnold and Taubes led to the foundation funding the Nutrition Science Initiative in [[San Diego]], where Taubes and  [[Peter Attia]] and are trying to find the cause of obesity.<ref name=Wired2017/><ref>{{cite news|title=The money behind the fight over healthy eating |date=October 7, 2015|author1=Purdy, Chase  |author2=Bottemiller Evich, Helena|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/10/the-money-behind-the-fight-over-healthy-eating-214517|publisher=Politico}}</ref> The foundation backs the Action Now Initiative (ANI) which in turn funds The Nutrition Coalition (TNC) which backed [[Nina Teicholz]] when she wrote an investigative piece for [[The BMJ]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nutrition-coalition.org/site/?page_id=6|title=About Us|publisher=The Nutrition Coalition|accessdate=October 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 the foundation funded the launch of the [[Center for Open Science]] with a $5.25 million grant and by 2017 had provided an additional $10 million in funding.<ref name=Wired2017/>   It also funded the launch of the [[Meta-Research Innovation Center at Stanford]] at Stanford University run by [[John Ioannidis]] and Steven Goodman to study ways to improve scientific research.<ref name=Wired2017/>  It also provided funding for the [[AllTrials]] initiative led in part by [[Ben Goldacre]].<ref name=Wired2017/>\n\nLJAF has published guidelines, based on the [[open science|Open Science Framework]], that anybody seeking research funding from them must follow.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.arnoldfoundation.org/sites/default/files/pdf/Guidelines%20for%20Research%20Funded%20by%20LJAF%207-29-2013.pdf|title = Guidelines for Investments in Research|publisher = Laura and John Arnold Foundation|date = July 29, 2013|accessdate = March 25, 2014|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140326090912/http://www.arnoldfoundation.org/sites/default/files/pdf/Guidelines%20for%20Research%20Funded%20by%20LJAF%207-29-2013.pdf|archive-date = March 26, 2014|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2017 it had given around $80 million in grants under its \"Research Integrity\" initiative.<ref name=Wired2017/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website}}\n\n[[Category:Foundations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2008]]\n", "name_user": "Whitmansylvia", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory and controversy:mostly punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arnold_Ventures_LLC"}
